{"term":"1956","caseName":"Arkansas & Louisiana Missouri Railway v. Amarillo-Borger Express","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1956/125","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - March 04, 1957","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren5/oral_argument_audio/13358","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 125, Arkansas & Louisiana Missouri Railway Company, et al., versus, Amarillo-Borger Express Incorporated, et al.","start":0,"stop":12.972,"duration":12.97},{"text":"Number 224, United States of America and Interstate Commerce Commission versus Amarillo-Borger Express Incorporated.","start":12.972,"stop":34.036,"duration":21.06},{"text":"Mr. Ginnane.","start":34.036,"stop":35.241,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":35.241,"stop":37.557,"duration":2.32},{"text":"I represent the appellants of the United States and the Interstate Commerce Commission.","start":37.557,"stop":42.748,"duration":5.19},{"text":"The appellants, Railroads, are represented by Mr. McDowell with whom I have agreed on the division of argument and the division at the time, if it please the Court.","start":42.748,"stop":55.195,"duration":12.45},{"text":"This case is here on direct appeal from the judgment of a three-judge District Court sitting in the Northern District of Texas.","start":55.195,"stop":65.521,"duration":10.33},{"text":"In general, the questions are whether the District Court aired in undertaking to review an order of the Interstate Commerce Commission vacating a prior rate suspension order.","start":65.521,"stop":79.188,"duration":13.67},{"text":"Secondly, in setting aside of that order for lack of findings and third --","start":79.188,"stop":84.586,"duration":5.4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Lack of -- lack of?","start":84.586,"stop":85.959,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Lack of findings.","start":85.959,"stop":88.189,"duration":2.23},{"text":"And third, in suspending or enjoining the use of carrier initiated rates after they had gone into effect.","start":88.189,"stop":98.654,"duration":10.47},{"text":"Now, these questions go to the heart of the statutory procedure for the making and suspension of rates.","start":98.654,"stop":108.673,"duration":10.02},{"text":"And that the Court will permit, instead of going into the immediate facts and issues of the case at the outset, I think it will be helpful if I outline first that general statutory procedure for the initiation and the suspension of rate.","start":108.673,"stop":123.965,"duration":15.29}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Without printing in anyway, you could get to ask this question now.","start":123.965,"stop":128.931,"duration":4.97},{"text":"But I just say (Inaudible) in the briefs and I'm hopeful to save us some time to deal with the questions (Inaudible)?","start":128.931,"stop":137.089,"duration":8.16}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":137.089,"stop":140.455,"duration":3.37},{"text":"This case involves rail rates and therefore, the rate provisions of part one of the Interstate Commerce Act.","start":140.455,"stop":148.222,"duration":7.77},{"text":"But similar provisions appear in parts two, three and four dealing with the rates of motor carriers, water carriers and freight forwarders.","start":148.222,"stop":159.67,"duration":11.45},{"text":"The Act generally contemplates that rates will be established upon the initiative of the carriers by filing with the Commission and publishing tariffs containing the new or changed rates.","start":159.67,"stop":175.084,"duration":15.41},{"text":"Thus, paragraph 3 of Section 6 provides that the railroads may file tariffs embodying rate changes to become effective upon 30 days notice to the Commission and to the public, unless the Commission in its discretion and for good cause shown allow such great changes to be made on less than 30 days notice.","start":175.084,"stop":197.317,"duration":22.23},{"text":"Now, prior to 1910, the Interstate Commerce Commission had no power to prevent railroad initiated rates from becoming effective.","start":197.317,"stop":208.648,"duration":11.33},{"text":"It could only set them aside as unlawful after a full hearing.","start":208.648,"stop":214.81,"duration":6.16},{"text":"It was in the Mann-Elkins Act of 1910 for the first time that Congress empowered the Commission to suspend railroad initiated rates before they became effective and for a specified period pending an investigation by the Commission into the lawfulness of the rates.","start":214.81,"stop":233.56,"duration":18.75},{"text":"That statutory period of suspension has -- has been changed by Congress from time to time.","start":233.56,"stop":238.798,"duration":5.24},{"text":"And at the present time under Section 15 paragraph (7) of the Act, the Commission may suspend rail rates for a period not to exceed in seven months.","start":238.798,"stop":248.651,"duration":9.85}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"The option of what you've said is that on the -- prior to Mann-Elkins, a rate could be put enforce would be collected x years, sometimes years might elapse before the rate challenge is unreasonable.","start":248.651,"stop":266.594,"duration":17.94},{"text":"It would then be set as -- then that'd be an order which we get into Court in some more time and if eventually the -- the Commission's order were sustained preparation proceedings that may begun for the past payments, is that right?","start":266.594,"stop":280.544,"duration":13.95}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, if the parties had survived.","start":280.544,"stop":282.121,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":282.121,"stop":282.974,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"And then applied to reductions (Inaudible) with increasing (Inaudible)","start":282.974,"stop":286.141,"duration":3.17}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Originally, it applied only to rate increases.","start":286.141,"stop":288.817,"duration":2.68},{"text":"As we came into an era of severe carrier competition, the statute was amended to apply to rate reductions --","start":288.817,"stop":294.507,"duration":5.69}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's discovered in 1920, am I right about that?","start":294.507,"stop":294.6,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"-- as well as freight rates.","start":294.6,"stop":297.967,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly, not Mann-Elkins.","start":297.967,"stop":299.277,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Mann-Elkins is applied only to the suspension of the rate increases.","start":299.277,"stop":303.614,"duration":4.34},{"text":"And later, it was amended to apply to rate decreases.","start":303.614,"stop":307.662,"duration":4.05},{"text":"And the only condition in the statute upon the -- upon the suspension of a rate is that the Commission shall deliver to the carrier or carriers effected thereby a statement in writing of the reasons for its suspension.","start":307.662,"stop":320.987,"duration":13.33},{"text":"And there is no requirement of a hearing prior to the exercise of the suspension power.","start":320.987,"stop":327.648,"duration":6.66},{"text":"At the end of the seven-month period --","start":327.648,"stop":329.514,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Meaning by that and I don't mean to interrupt you except to elucidate if I can.","start":329.514,"stop":333.633,"duration":4.12},{"text":"Meaning by that, the Commission could do that on its own initiative to suspend or if it's moved thereto?","start":333.633,"stop":341.13,"duration":7.5}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, without -- without any prior notice or hearing.","start":341.13,"stop":346.221,"duration":5.09},{"text":"In that -- in that connection, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, at the present time, the Commission exercises its rate suspension powers, almost entirely upon the application of shipping or competing carriers that rather than upon its own motion.","start":346.221,"stop":362.471,"duration":16.25},{"text":"At the end of the seven-month suspension period, the railroad may make -- put the rates into effect without winning for the completion of the Commission's investigation if it's still going on.","start":362.471,"stop":373.328,"duration":10.86},{"text":"And once the rates have become effective, the carrier must observe under the provisions of Section 6.","start":373.328,"stop":382.213,"duration":8.89},{"text":"I should say that almost identical rate suspension provisions appear in the Natural Gas Act, the Federal Power Act, the Communications Act and the Civil Aeronautics Act.","start":382.213,"stop":392.92,"duration":10.71},{"text":"The Commission has created both an organization and the procedure for handling these rate suspension matters.","start":392.92,"stop":399.536,"duration":6.62},{"text":"Pursuant to its delegation powers under Section 17, it has delegated to the Board of Suspension, consisting of five employees of the Commission, the power to act upon protest, as they are called, which seek the suspension of rates.","start":399.536,"stop":418.886,"duration":19.35},{"text":"Both protestants and the respondent carriers may appeal from the decision of the Board of Suspension to Division 2 of the Commission, Division 2 consisting of three members of the Commission who are responsible under the full commission for rate matters generally.","start":418.886,"stop":436.212,"duration":17.33},{"text":"By regulations published in the federal register, the Commission has prescribed the procedure which I would like to describe very briefly.","start":436.212,"stop":444.449,"duration":8.24},{"text":"These regulations provide that the proceedings before the Board of Suspension shall be informal.","start":444.449,"stop":449.061,"duration":4.61},{"text":"No transcription of its proceedings is made, subpoenas are not issued, olds are not administered.","start":449.061,"stop":455.916,"duration":6.86},{"text":"Protest must be in writing or in emergencies in telegraphic form.","start":455.916,"stop":461.341,"duration":5.43},{"text":"They must be filed with the Commission and served upon the carrier which initiated the rates, at least 12 days before the effective date of the rates.","start":461.341,"stop":470.45,"duration":9.11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All of it.","start":470.45,"stop":471.368,"duration":0.92},{"text":"All of the suspension brought home, not only to the carrier, I suppose he gets a while to the shipping public and the region of the tariff.","start":471.368,"stop":479.495,"duration":8.13}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"A notice is put on the tariff file.","start":479.495,"stop":482.729,"duration":3.23},{"text":"A notice is put in the tariff file, the Commission's tariff file.","start":482.729,"stop":487.05,"duration":4.32}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- and how did the shippers or shippers on the division gets notice of it?","start":487.05,"stop":492.33,"duration":5.28},{"text":"Is there any formal way of publication or anything?","start":492.33,"stop":496.727,"duration":4.4}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"A shipper -- under the Commission's tariff rules, the carrier is required to file a supplement and that supplement must be filed both with the Commission and with the -- the various (Inaudible) stations, the Court has published the tariffs.","start":496.727,"stop":511.36,"duration":14.63},{"text":"Thus, you'll find the supplement that -- that carrying notice of the suspension in the same place so that you find the tariff itself.","start":511.36,"stop":518.116,"duration":6.76}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The body of shippers would have -- would find out.","start":518.116,"stop":522.008,"duration":3.89}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Believe me, sir, the -- the organized shipper groups and the organized competing carrier groups watch these things on the power to our basis.","start":522.008,"stop":533.292,"duration":11.28},{"text":"And the carrier may file a reply to the protest, whereas in the instant case, the Suspension Board refuses to suspend rates.","start":533.292,"stop":543.769,"duration":10.48},{"text":"The protestants or their shippers or competing carriers may file with Division 2, a petition for reconsideration which must be filed at least two days prior to the effective date of the tariffs.","start":543.769,"stop":556.433,"duration":12.66},{"text":"Both the Board and the Division act upon the basis of written protest and written replies frequently supplemented by informal conferences with the Board.","start":556.433,"stop":569.553,"duration":13.12},{"text":"And it's very significant, we think, for the issues in this case to note that the Commission's procedure in order to give shippers and competing carries an opportunity to look at the new tariffs and to formulate their protest, the result of that is the statutory period of 30 days is now down to a period of 12 days, sometimes a little more for consideration by the Commission.","start":569.553,"stop":594.803,"duration":25.25},{"text":"And this 12-day period must include the carrier's opportunity to reply to the protest, deliberation and decision by the Suspension Board and appeal to and decision by Division 2.","start":594.803,"stop":609.395,"duration":14.59},{"text":"Also, this organization must operate not only rapidly but to handle a large volume of matters.","start":609.395,"stop":616.82,"duration":7.43},{"text":"We point out in our brief that during the year ended October 31, 1955, 4800 protests were filed against 4000 tariffs of rail motor and water carriers.","start":616.82,"stop":630.324,"duration":13.5},{"text":"Of these 2100 were suspended in whole or in part, 1300 were permitted to become effective and 600 were withdrawn for one reason or another, such as the tariff was withdrawn or the protests were withdrawn.","start":630.324,"stop":642.268,"duration":11.94}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The scheme applies to all three chapters?","start":642.268,"stop":646.261,"duration":3.99}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Applies to the rates of freight forwarders.","start":646.261,"stop":648.609,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"On --","start":648.609,"stop":649.116,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Four chapters.","start":649.116,"stop":649.993,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Four chapters --","start":649.993,"stop":650.872,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Including part four dealing with freight forwarders.","start":650.872,"stop":653.755,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Same -- the same agencies.","start":653.755,"stop":655.368,"duration":1.61},{"text":"The same -- the same -- this Suspension Board and --","start":655.368,"stop":658.767,"duration":3.4}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":658.767,"stop":659.149,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and number two?","start":659.149,"stop":660.449,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":660.449,"stop":662.436,"duration":1.99},{"text":"The Suspension Board in relation to handle all four types of rate matters.","start":662.436,"stop":667.325,"duration":4.89},{"text":"So in the brief, the suspension procedure is characterized by informality, speed of decision and a tremendous volume of rates.","start":667.325,"stop":676.555,"duration":9.23},{"text":"Now, in the instant case, the appellant, Railroads, on or about August 12, 1955 filed reduced rates on carbon black moving from Texas and adjacent points to consuming centers in the north such as Akron, Ohio.","start":676.555,"stop":695.222,"duration":18.67},{"text":"And these rates were to become effective on September 24.","start":695.222,"stop":700.668,"duration":5.45},{"text":"On September 8, 10 and 11, several motor carrier rate bureaus and one motor carrier filed protest with the Commission.","start":700.668,"stop":709.827,"duration":9.16},{"text":"On September 22, two days before the rates were to become effective, the Suspension -- the Suspension Board refused to suspend but directed an investigation into the rates.","start":709.827,"stop":724.156,"duration":14.33},{"text":"The protestants appeal immediately to Division 2 which on September 23, the day before the rates were to become effective, suspended the rates for the full statutory period of seven months which would have suspended them until April 23, 1956.","start":724.156,"stop":743.812,"duration":19.66},{"text":"Following month in October 1955, the appellant, Railroads, petitioned Division 2 for reconsideration and for vacation of its suspension order.","start":743.812,"stop":754.739,"duration":10.93},{"text":"And on November 14, Division 2 entered a second order vacating its prior suspension order as of November 24 but continuing the investigation into the lawfulness of the rates.","start":754.739,"stop":769.728,"duration":14.99},{"text":"On November 23, the present action was commenced by the, appellee motor carriers in the Texas court.","start":769.728,"stop":778.784,"duration":9.06},{"text":"And on that same day, November 23, the day before the rates were to become effective, Judge Atwell denied their application for a temporary restraining order.","start":778.784,"stop":790.145,"duration":11.36},{"text":"After a hearing before the three-judge court, it rendered its judgment on January 24, which set aside as void ab initio, the Commission's order of November 14 vacating its prior suspension order.","start":790.145,"stop":809.292,"duration":19.15},{"text":"Remanding the matter to the Commission for further proceedings as though the order of November 14, 1955 had never been entered and prohibiting use of a new reduced rates on carbon black under the suspension order until the suspension order shall have been rescinded or modified by lawful action of the Interstate Commerce Commission.","start":809.292,"stop":834.508,"duration":25.22},{"text":"The judgment is set forth on the record at page 61.","start":834.508,"stop":841.384,"duration":6.88},{"text":"The District Court set aside the Commission's order which vacated its prior -- prior suspension order on the ground that the vacating order was not accompanied by sufficient findings.","start":841.384,"stop":857.663,"duration":16.28},{"text":"We contend, first of all, that the Commission's order vacating the prior suspension order was not subject to review at all.","start":857.663,"stop":869.56,"duration":11.9},{"text":"And later, we will contend that even assuming that it was subject to review that the vacating order was not required to be accompanied by findings.","start":869.56,"stop":878.32,"duration":8.76}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is the statute silent on the question of finding or is that --","start":878.32,"stop":882.441,"duration":4.12}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"The only thing --","start":882.441,"stop":882.867,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- a matter in controversy?","start":882.867,"stop":884.793,"duration":1.93},{"text":"Well, don't -- don't let (Inaudible).","start":884.793,"stop":887.126,"duration":2.33}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"The only --","start":887.126,"stop":887.309,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Don't answer yet (Voice Overlap) --","start":887.309,"stop":887.807,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the nearest thing there is to set your requirement of the statute is the requirement in the suspension provision on paragraph 7 of Section 15.","start":887.807,"stop":896.288,"duration":8.48},{"text":"That if the Commission suspends, it shall give a statement or written statement of its reasons for suspending to the carrier whose rates are suspended, otherwise, the rate provisions of the Act are silent as to reasons or findings.","start":896.288,"stop":909.792,"duration":13.5}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Where was that from your point of view satisfied?","start":909.792,"stop":913.996,"duration":4.2},{"text":"I'm not arguing, but where was that document which gave the carrier reasons?","start":913.996,"stop":919.175,"duration":5.18}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"At the --","start":919.175,"stop":923.287,"duration":4.11}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Record 86 or 46.","start":923.287,"stop":930.597,"duration":7.31}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You have that on page four?","start":930.597,"stop":933.526,"duration":2.93}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Beginning at the bottom of page 5 of the record, paragraph -- beginning about six lines in the bottom of page and contending to the top of page 6.","start":933.526,"stop":947.067,"duration":13.54}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And what is the specific provision of the statute?","start":947.067,"stop":952.562,"duration":5.5}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"That would be in our brief at page 47 beginning about the fifth line on top of the page, and pending such hearing and the decision thereon, Commission upon filing with such schedule and delivering to the carrier or carriers effected thereby a statement in writing of its reasons for such suspension.","start":952.562,"stop":978.753,"duration":26.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, did the court below say you didn't give reasons or you didn't make findings?","start":978.753,"stop":983.47,"duration":4.72}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"The court below said that our order vacating the suspension order must be -- must be accompanied by findings.","start":983.47,"stop":989.527,"duration":6.06}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":989.527,"stop":990.313,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"It based that variously on the Administrative Procedure Act --","start":990.313,"stop":992.905,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but it did find --","start":992.905,"stop":993.09,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and such decisions of this Court as Florida.","start":993.09,"stop":995.165,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- findings in the technical sense, I mean if you find anything.","start":995.165,"stop":998.318,"duration":3.15}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":998.318,"stop":998.767,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":998.767,"stop":999.023,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Stanley Reed","textObjs":[{"text":"Are those findings necessary even though there was no hearing before us?","start":999.023,"stop":1001.882,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"We contend that they are not, sir.","start":1001.882,"stop":1003.538,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1003.538,"stop":1004.794,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"First of all -- first of all, we will contend --","start":1004.794,"stop":1007.422,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":1007.422,"stop":1007.509,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that the order was not reviewable.","start":1007.509,"stop":1009.281,"duration":1.77},{"text":"Secondly, assuming reviewability that the order should not have been set aside and that findings were not required.","start":1009.281,"stop":1016.349,"duration":7.07}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any different to the reviewability of the original order suspending and the -- the revoking order?","start":1016.349,"stop":1025.671,"duration":9.32}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"We would think not, although that issue is not before the Court, strictly speaking.","start":1025.671,"stop":1030.208,"duration":4.54}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1030.208,"stop":1031.288,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I gather it's conceded that the vacation order was not supported by affirmative findings.","start":1031.288,"stop":1039.156,"duration":7.87},{"text":"We would say that the Commission made clear a -- a finding in this sense that upon reconsideration of its suspension order but the mere fact of vacating it.","start":1039.156,"stop":1053.406,"duration":14.25},{"text":"It was in effect saying that it was not sufficiently clear, it was not sufficient -- it wasn't sufficiently convinced that the rates were probably unlawful --","start":1053.406,"stop":1063.64,"duration":10.23}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I know.","start":1063.64,"stop":1063.848,"duration":0.21},{"text":"What I mean --","start":1063.848,"stop":1064.097,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to justify interference with the carrier statutory right to initiate its finding.","start":1064.097,"stop":1067.758,"duration":3.66}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But my question was this, Mr. Ginnane.","start":1067.758,"stop":1070,"duration":2.24},{"text":"Is there any affirmative finding supporting the vacation?","start":1070,"stop":1074.294,"duration":4.29}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"In effect, the Commission said after considering the petition for reconsideration, and the reply is that -- and the replies to those petitions and for a good cause, we vacate our prior part.","start":1074.294,"stop":1085.358,"duration":11.06}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's all there is.","start":1085.358,"stop":1086.288,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Practically verbatim, sir.","start":1086.288,"stop":1089.691,"duration":3.4},{"text":"First, we contend that the order was not reviewable at all.","start":1089.691,"stop":1093.746,"duration":4.06},{"text":"We submit that the rate suspension power was deliberately entrusted by Congress to the exclusive discretion of the Commission.","start":1093.746,"stop":1101.969,"duration":8.22},{"text":"And starting with the language of the statute itself, paragraph 7 of Section 15, it says that the Commission may suspend rates and that wasn't just an -- an accidental choice of words as between “may” and “shall” because the report of the Senate Committee on interstate commerce in reporting the original Mann-Elkins bill says that the Commission should, in its discretion, be empowered to suspend rates pending investigation.","start":1101.969,"stop":1128.697,"duration":26.73},{"text":"And until the instant case, the lower federal courts had consistently refused to review in the Commission orders suspending rates and in one case in order vacating a prior suspension order.","start":1128.697,"stop":1142.643,"duration":13.95}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you carry that to the point of saying that even there is no judicial review even to determine whether the Commission has been procedurally correct, then there's no power to review the merits of a suspension order?","start":1142.643,"stop":1159.517,"duration":16.87},{"text":"Is the Court also prevented from deciding whether the Commission has complied with its own rules, whatever they may be with the statute, whatever the requirements of the statutes are?","start":1159.517,"stop":1172.651,"duration":13.13}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"I think so, sir.","start":1172.651,"stop":1173.385,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You do.","start":1173.385,"stop":1174.619,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":1174.619,"stop":1174.71,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) any business looking into this business -- looking into this matter at all?","start":1174.71,"stop":1178.732,"duration":4.02}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm afraid of that word \"never.\"","start":1178.732,"stop":1182.156,"duration":3.42},{"text":"And later, I shall discuss briefly two cases which came up under the federal power and -- and where -- what -- which involved rate suspension matters to be sure, but it went right to the heart of whether the -- the Commission in those cases had authority to act at all.","start":1182.156,"stop":1197.655,"duration":15.5},{"text":"In one case, the issue was whether it had the suspended rates for longer than the period permitted by Congress.","start":1197.655,"stop":1204.762,"duration":7.11},{"text":"I don't challenge that result.","start":1204.762,"stop":1206.605,"duration":1.84},{"text":"What we contend is that here where the Commission is exercising a power which it admittedly has enacting within the statutory limits of that power that Congress intended it to be unreviewable.","start":1206.605,"stop":1218.493,"duration":11.89}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Ginnane, would it disturb the architecture of your argument if you told us -- if you summarize what the judicial situation is today, the Mann-Elkins Act of 1910?","start":1218.493,"stop":1232.099,"duration":13.61},{"text":"We're now in 1957, that's 47 years, and it comes to me as a great surprise that this is not a separate question.","start":1232.099,"stop":1241.6,"duration":9.5},{"text":"What is the judicial -- here is the balance sheet of the --","start":1241.6,"stop":1245.51,"duration":3.91}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly.","start":1245.51,"stop":1245.634,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- judicial situation today.","start":1245.634,"stop":1247.578,"duration":1.94},{"text":"On this question, namely, whether it's reviewable, except in the way in which you indicated if they suspend it for two years when the Congress says 90 days because they get suspended for two years, how that gives you anything.","start":1247.578,"stop":1260.488,"duration":12.91}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"To begin with, Your Honor, the question has not been before this Court.","start":1260.488,"stop":1265.327,"duration":4.84},{"text":"There are several cases cited in our brief, three-judge courts prior to this case had refused to -- had refused to review orders denying suspension or vacating prior suspension orders.","start":1265.327,"stop":1281.474,"duration":16.15},{"text":"And they did so specifically on the ground that this rate suspension orders were entrusted entirely to the discretion of the Commission and were not subject to review.","start":1281.474,"stop":1292.804,"duration":11.33},{"text":"Now, following this case, there have been two cases following --","start":1292.804,"stop":1297.29,"duration":4.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did this case -- there has been no court, if I follow you, has entertained a bill like this.","start":1297.29,"stop":1306.996,"duration":9.71}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1306.996,"stop":1307.707,"duration":0.71},{"text":"Now, I should --","start":1307.707,"stop":1308.716,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did it go --","start":1308.716,"stop":1309.084,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"-- I should to refer --","start":1309.084,"stop":1309.679,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- is there any question of -- did it gone that it's a non-judicially reviewable or that at the state it isn't at the particular state order reviewable?","start":1309.679,"stop":1318.859,"duration":9.18},{"text":"They simply said this is a suspension filed after the Commission and you have to wait until they do something about the tariff intrinsically, is that it?","start":1318.859,"stop":1327.663,"duration":8.8}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"After a hearing.","start":1327.663,"stop":1333.075,"duration":5.41},{"text":"Following the decision in this case, the same Court in the Dixie Carriers case, which the Government has also appealed to this Court, arrived at the same result.","start":1333.075,"stop":1343.34,"duration":10.26},{"text":"And the three-judge court in -- in the Southern District of New York, the Long Island Railroad case also followed at the instant case.","start":1343.34,"stop":1351.577,"duration":8.24}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What was that case?","start":1351.577,"stop":1353.786,"duration":2.21},{"text":"Do you know, can you turn it for us?","start":1353.786,"stop":1357.561,"duration":3.77}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"It's in the Eastern District of New York, the Long Island Railroad Company against United States.","start":1357.561,"stop":1362.742,"duration":5.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"When was it?","start":1362.742,"stop":1363.24,"duration":0.5},{"text":"Have you got the citation?","start":1363.24,"stop":1366.413,"duration":3.17}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't have an official citation --","start":1366.413,"stop":1367.548,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there a reason that I don't --","start":1367.548,"stop":1369.132,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"-- decided on May 9, 1956.","start":1369.132,"stop":1371.676,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1371.676,"stop":1372.035,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, subsequent to the decision in this case.","start":1372.035,"stop":1374.898,"duration":2.86},{"text":"Then, there had been those two Federal Power Commission cases involving what seemed to us to be entirely -- an entirely different sort of thing, that jurisdiction to suspend it all.","start":1374.898,"stop":1384.722,"duration":9.82},{"text":"And then, there have been three cases decided this past year by the Fifth Circuit under the Natural Gas Act.","start":1384.722,"stop":1393.801,"duration":9.08},{"text":"It was probably a large group of cases under the Natural Gas Act in which this Court denied certiorari a few months ago.","start":1393.801,"stop":1400.05,"duration":6.25}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Wasn't the dissenter there the writer of the opinion in this field?","start":1400.05,"stop":1404.072,"duration":4.02}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, Judge Brown of the Fifth Circuit.","start":1404.072,"stop":1406.834,"duration":2.76}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Judge Brown.","start":1406.834,"stop":1407.729,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1407.729,"stop":1409.629,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Long Island?","start":1409.629,"stop":1412.54,"duration":2.91},{"text":"What's the name of the Long Island case?","start":1412.54,"stop":1414.823,"duration":2.28}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Long -- Long Island Railroad Company v. United States.","start":1414.823,"stop":1420.905,"duration":6.08},{"text":"We would be glad to -- to --","start":1420.905,"stop":1422.441,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't find it in your brief, do I?","start":1422.441,"stop":1424.092,"duration":1.65},{"text":"Should I?","start":1424.092,"stop":1428.095,"duration":4}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think it's there.","start":1428.095,"stop":1430.064,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Who were the judges?","start":1430.064,"stop":1430.777,"duration":0.71},{"text":"Do you know?","start":1430.777,"stop":1436.534,"duration":5.76}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"The judges were -- District Judges Byers and Bruchhausen with Judge Swan dissenting.","start":1436.534,"stop":1443.857,"duration":7.32}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't think he decides (Inaudible)","start":1443.857,"stop":1445.625,"duration":1.77},{"text":"I don't know about these cases.","start":1445.625,"stop":1451.206,"duration":5.58},{"text":"And they rested on this case, do I get that --","start":1451.206,"stop":1453.244,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, they very largely followed this case.","start":1453.244,"stop":1454.812,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't think if it's not reported, perhaps, you will have copies of it.","start":1454.812,"stop":1459.168,"duration":4.36}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"We will be glad listen to them.","start":1459.168,"stop":1466.737,"duration":7.57},{"text":"It is in 140 F.Supp., but I'm sorry none of us have the page number, 140 F.Supp.","start":1466.737,"stop":1474.171,"duration":7.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you very much.","start":1474.171,"stop":1474.925,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) Long Island?","start":1474.925,"stop":1476.37,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Long Island Railroad Company v. United States.","start":1476.37,"stop":1482.65,"duration":6.28},{"text":"Page 823, we finally have it, 140 F.Supp., 823.","start":1482.65,"stop":1486.981,"duration":4.33}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":1486.981,"stop":1489.885,"duration":2.9}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Also, we think it's settled beyond citation that the federal courts will not review preliminary, procedural or interlocutory orders of federal agencies.","start":1489.885,"stop":1501.326,"duration":11.44},{"text":"And it seems to us that the actual discretion in suspending or refusing to suspend the rate or in vacating a prior suspension order is merely preliminary and ancillary to its full and formal investigation and to whether the rates are lawful.","start":1501.326,"stop":1518.535,"duration":17.21},{"text":"And that's emphasized by the fact that in making these suspension decisions, the Commission must act informally or rapidly on the basis of admitted what often turns out to be incomplete information.","start":1518.535,"stop":1530.513,"duration":11.98}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It is the standard rate that an increase in a rate, whether it's utility rates or railroad rate or ordinary in a supreme utility, there are usually ways of protecting the consumer.","start":1530.513,"stop":1546.187,"duration":15.67},{"text":"If you suspend an increase in rate here, there's no way of protecting their carrier, is there?","start":1546.187,"stop":1551.505,"duration":5.32}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"If this is -- let me practice.","start":1551.505,"stop":1555.113,"duration":3.61},{"text":"At -- at the present time --","start":1555.113,"stop":1556.103,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If you suspend their desire for an increase, the reasonableness of which may just relatively justify or sustain by the Commission.","start":1556.103,"stop":1566.527,"duration":10.42},{"text":"In the meantime, they're out of pocket or what may be found to be a reasonable rate, isn't that the problem?","start":1566.527,"stop":1572.166,"duration":5.64}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct, sir.","start":1572.166,"stop":1573.27,"duration":1.1},{"text":"But I should give you this by way of background.","start":1573.27,"stop":1575.913,"duration":2.64},{"text":"That at -- that in recent years, the great majority of these rate suspension matters endowed rate decreases.","start":1575.913,"stop":1585.155,"duration":9.24},{"text":"And of course, there is no way of whether the Commission suspends or does not suspend that there's no way it can protect the initiating carrier or the competing carrier against lost in the event the Commission has made a mistake in suspending or not suspending.","start":1585.155,"stop":1600.252,"duration":15.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But I don't know why you say that.","start":1600.252,"stop":1601.964,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a delicate drastic power.","start":1601.964,"stop":1603.554,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1603.554,"stop":1607.921,"duration":4.37}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, they mentioned in response to Mr. Justice Douglas question, the Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit has recently held in the group of cases under the Natural Gas Act that orders of the Federal Power Commission suspending rates are not subject to judicial review.","start":1607.921,"stop":1624.886,"duration":16.96},{"text":"And one of those cases, the Humble Oil & Refining case, in which this Court denied certiorari, the Fifth Circuit characterized this type of order in words which we think fit here better than anything we can say.","start":1624.886,"stop":1637.553,"duration":12.67},{"text":"It said, \"The order in question is in no proper sense, a definitive order.","start":1637.553,"stop":1642.078,"duration":4.52},{"text":"It is a mere procedural step taking at the inception of and not upon the completion of the administrative process.\"","start":1642.078,"stop":1648.541,"duration":6.46},{"text":"A realistic appraise of the order and the function it performs demonstrates that it is interlocutory and that its issuance had but one objective in view to maintain the status quo between the seller and purchaser pending the exercise of the Commission statutory jurisdiction to inquire the lawfulness of the rates.","start":1648.541,"stop":1669.02,"duration":20.48},{"text":"In this discretionary and preliminary character of rate suspension actions, it seems to us, is emphasized by the fact that Congress has provided two full administrative remedies for shippers and carriers who are -- who object to new rates.","start":1669.02,"stop":1688.316,"duration":19.3},{"text":"In this case, the appellee motor carriers could have participated and -- and in fact, they did participate in the Commission's full investigation and hearing of the lawfulness of these new rail rates.","start":1688.316,"stop":1702.02,"duration":13.7},{"text":"Moreover, if the Commission had not instituted an investigation under Section 15, as it did, if it had not done so, then the objective motor carriers or any shippers who wanted to object could have filed a formal complaint with the Commission under Section 13.","start":1702.02,"stop":1718.457,"duration":16.44},{"text":"And the Commission would have been required to undertake a full investigation in hearing into the lawfulness of the rates.","start":1718.457,"stop":1725.333,"duration":6.88},{"text":"And this Court held long ago in United States v. Merchants Association in 243 U.S., that these remedies provided by Sections 13 and 15 are administrative remedies which must be exhausted by shippers and by carriers before they can invoke judicial remedies.","start":1725.333,"stop":1747.444,"duration":22.11},{"text":"As a matter of fact, that will -- that was laid down in that case in a more drastic situation on this.","start":1747.444,"stop":1753.686,"duration":6.24},{"text":"That was a case where involving the long-haul, short-haul provisions of the Act.","start":1753.686,"stop":1763.033,"duration":9.35},{"text":"Intermediate communities and shippers protested.","start":1763.033,"stop":1766.098,"duration":3.07},{"text":"The Commission has granted relief from the Section 4 prohibition against charging more for a long-haul than for a shorter haul.","start":1766.098,"stop":1774.108,"duration":8.01},{"text":"And this Court held that not even the intervening communities and shippers could challenge the Section 4 order.","start":1774.108,"stop":1782.77,"duration":8.66},{"text":"There was no question but that they were effective, but they must exhaust their remedy either under Section 13 or under Section 15 before they could come in to Court.","start":1782.77,"stop":1795.289,"duration":12.52},{"text":"We submit that the cases relied upon by the appellees as supporting their reviewability of suspension actions are easily distinguished.","start":1795.289,"stop":1803.29,"duration":8},{"text":"And I'll mention just one for an example.","start":1803.29,"stop":1805.535,"duration":2.25},{"text":"That's the Utah Fuel Company v. Bituminous Coal Commission at 306 of this court's reports.","start":1805.535,"stop":1812.301,"duration":6.77},{"text":"That case on its face involved the claim of injury of a type which as this Court recognized, Congress had not provided any remedy.","start":1812.301,"stop":1821.369,"duration":9.07},{"text":"In contrast here, Congress has provided remedies in Sections 13 and 15 of the Act which this Court, 50 years ago, said it must be exhausted.","start":1821.369,"stop":1832.178,"duration":10.81},{"text":"However, the appellee's most specific reliance is upon the Fourth Circuit's decision in the Atlantic Seaboard Corporation case and the Tenth Circuit's decision, in the Phillips Petroleum v. Federal Power Commission.","start":1832.178,"stop":1847.397,"duration":15.22},{"text":"Now, the Atlantic Seaboard Corporation case involved the issue of whether the Federal Power Commission had suspended rates for longer than the five-month period authorized by the Natural Gas Act.","start":1847.397,"stop":1860.909,"duration":13.51},{"text":"The Phillips case involved the question whether the Federal Power Commission's rate suspension power could be applied to rate increases which resulted from an escalator clause in a contract which was in effect prior to this Court's basic decision in Phillips Petroleum v. State of Wisconsin.","start":1860.909,"stop":1880.17,"duration":19.26},{"text":"And it seems to us that those cases are distinguishable and that they can go right to the question of whether the Commission is -- as to whether agency was acting within its statutory authority, within the statutory jurisdiction, whereas this case involves the exercise of admitted power to suspend.","start":1880.17,"stop":1901.755,"duration":21.59},{"text":"The opinion of the District Court particularly at pages 53 and 55, in the case that it thought that Section 10 of the Administrative Procedure Act, subjected orders such as rate suspension orders to review.","start":1901.755,"stop":1918.487,"duration":16.73},{"text":"We disagree.","start":1918.487,"stop":1921.24,"duration":2.75},{"text":"In our brief, we point out that the review provision of Section 10 of the APA, a purport by the introductory clause accepts so far as statutes preclude judicial review and to agency action is by law committed to agency discretion.","start":1921.24,"stop":1938.87,"duration":17.63},{"text":"We point out that this Court has repeatedly held in a serious of recent cases that this introductory clause -- clauses limit and qualify the other provisions of Section 10.","start":1938.87,"stop":1953.133,"duration":14.26},{"text":"We also point out that Section 10 specifically avoids making it reviewable, the preliminary and procedural interlocutory orders of agencies.","start":1953.133,"stop":1970.406,"duration":17.27},{"text":"Thus, Section 10 (c) provides that such orders shall be directly reviewable by the courts only where Congress so prescribes and Congress has not so required here.","start":1970.406,"stop":1981.041,"duration":10.63},{"text":"And on the last term, this Court noted in the Colorado Interstate Gas case, that the Administrative Procedure Act purports to strengthen them but rather than to weaken the rule that administrative remedies must be exhausted before it resort to judicial remedies.","start":1981.041,"stop":1997.389,"duration":16.35},{"text":"And so we submit that nothing in the law, either in the Administrative Procedure Act or into the whole body of law developed by this Court on -- to reviewability of agency action supports the decision below that the Commission's order vacating a prior suspension order was reviewable.","start":1997.389,"stop":2017.153,"duration":19.76}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, suppose it suggested that they have exhausted everything here.","start":2017.153,"stop":2021.549,"duration":4.4},{"text":"The only thing to -- the only thing that's left is the disposition of the merits of the rate of the proposed tariff.","start":2021.549,"stop":2030.888,"duration":9.34},{"text":"What is the -- what law can they do on this question of suspension (Inaudible)","start":2030.888,"stop":2036.494,"duration":5.61}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Pursue the remedies which Congress has given them under --","start":2036.494,"stop":2038.765,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Which is?","start":2038.765,"stop":2040.669,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Participate in the Commission's formal proceeding --","start":2040.669,"stop":2044.444,"duration":3.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Under substantive faith.","start":2044.444,"stop":2044.783,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"-- during in the law -- into lawfulness of the rates.","start":2044.783,"stop":2046.897,"duration":2.11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Great.","start":2046.897,"stop":2047.503,"duration":0.61},{"text":"Well, but so far as -- so far as what the Commission has done best far or the -- the impact, the consequence of suspending a rate, they've exhausted all there is on that --","start":2047.503,"stop":2063.67,"duration":16.17}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, sir.","start":2063.67,"stop":2064.062,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- on that -- in that process and nothing left for that to do except --","start":2064.062,"stop":2067.781,"duration":3.72}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2067.781,"stop":2068.194,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to await a determination and award by -- a report by the Commission on the merits.","start":2068.194,"stop":2073.494,"duration":5.3}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"The same as there's nothing private litigants and -- and -- before the courts can -- can do when judge grants or refuses to grant a temporary restraining order --","start":2073.494,"stop":2082.795,"duration":9.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's --","start":2082.795,"stop":2083.007,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to the most extraordinary situations, there is no appeal.","start":2083.007,"stop":2087.592,"duration":4.59}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Maybe so.","start":2087.592,"stop":2088.295,"duration":0.7},{"text":"But I -- I don't think it helps many to say they must exhaust the administrative remedy.","start":2088.295,"stop":2092.505,"duration":4.21},{"text":"They've got an administrative remedy to exhaust on this action (Voice Overlap) --","start":2092.505,"stop":2097.596,"duration":5.09}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"That is quite correct.","start":2097.596,"stop":2102.532,"duration":4.94},{"text":"My colleague, Mr. McDowell, in his portion of our argument will -- will point out that the practical consequences are trying to fit the most limited form of judicial review into the statutory time -- timetable for -- for making the rates and for the exercise of the suspension power.","start":2102.532,"stop":2123.15,"duration":20.62},{"text":"The dilemma has created for all the concerned.","start":2123.15,"stop":2125.898,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. -- You come indeed -- probably it did but I didn't get that.","start":2125.898,"stop":2130.18,"duration":4.28},{"text":"The -- when did this litigation begin in the courts?","start":2130.18,"stop":2134.754,"duration":4.57}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"On November 23, the complaint was filed.","start":2134.754,"stop":2137.134,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Of -- of 1950?","start":2137.134,"stop":2138.699,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"1955.","start":2138.699,"stop":2139.358,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"1955.","start":2139.358,"stop":2141.273,"duration":1.91},{"text":"We're now in -- in March 1957.","start":2141.273,"stop":2145.329,"duration":4.06},{"text":"The disposition of the merits are held up, aren't they?","start":2145.329,"stop":2147.793,"duration":2.46}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2147.793,"stop":2148.523,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- you go on with the hearing?","start":2148.523,"stop":2151.201,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the Commission continued with the full investigation and hearing.","start":2151.201,"stop":2153.991,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And is that on --","start":2153.991,"stop":2154.586,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- and quite a few months ago, the rates here involved were sustained as lawful.","start":2154.586,"stop":2159.519,"duration":4.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They were?","start":2159.519,"stop":2160.273,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2160.273,"stop":2161.115,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But then, that -- I should think that brings to the very forefront of Mr. Justice Harlan's question.","start":2161.115,"stop":2166.081,"duration":4.97},{"text":"What are we deciding here, an abstract question?","start":2166.081,"stop":2169.112,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"No, indeed.","start":2169.112,"stop":2171.385,"duration":2.27},{"text":"We --","start":2171.385,"stop":2171.411,"duration":0.03}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, I understand we're deciding here if this goes one way, it will tell the Commission one thing.","start":2171.411,"stop":2176.45,"duration":5.04},{"text":"If it goes beyond that and so far as this litigation is concern, is that question alive?","start":2176.45,"stop":2181.832,"duration":5.38}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"As far as this litigation is concern, the question is alive as we see it.","start":2181.832,"stop":2186.022,"duration":4.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":2186.022,"stop":2186.65,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"The judgment of the District Court was -- was deliberately framed.","start":2186.65,"stop":2192.055,"duration":5.4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But -- was what?","start":2192.055,"stop":2192.925,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"That it was deliberately framed to set aside the Commission's order vacating its prior suspension order ab initio, to restore things as they were as though the vacation order had never been entered.","start":2192.925,"stop":2206.642,"duration":13.72},{"text":"And that as a result, the railroads are -- are under an obligation to collect from their shippers that during the period of some weeks that the new reduced rates were in effect.","start":2206.642,"stop":2219.862,"duration":13.22},{"text":"The difference between the --","start":2219.862,"stop":2221.495,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That is --","start":2221.495,"stop":2221.852,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"-- former higher charges and the -- the reduced rates which were later filed.","start":2221.852,"stop":2229.801,"duration":7.95},{"text":"So, it's -- what seemed to be far from academic with respect to the railroads whose rates were involved.","start":2229.801,"stop":2237.637,"duration":7.84}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And as far as these two parties are concerned, what is certainly academic, this is an action by one of the parties, some step -- one of these parties has got vague against the third party.","start":2237.637,"stop":2251.021,"duration":13.38}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"It -- if this gentleman stays in effect.","start":2251.021,"stop":2252.831,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2252.831,"stop":2256.879,"duration":4.05},{"text":"So far as the party is involved in this litigation is concerned, what seize that answer is the moot in this problem?","start":2256.879,"stop":2266.069,"duration":9.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Who would collect what?","start":2266.069,"stop":2267.171,"duration":1.1},{"text":"Just tell me that again.","start":2267.171,"stop":2269.949,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"The railroads are obligated to collect from the shippers, from their shippers.","start":2269.949,"stop":2274.338,"duration":4.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The railroad --","start":2274.338,"stop":2274.51,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"They ship on -- on the reduced rates during the period that they were in effect prior to the judgment of this case.","start":2274.51,"stop":2283.113,"duration":8.6},{"text":"The difference between the -- the former higher rates which were in effect and the lower rate -- and the lower rates which they filed with the Commission and which are the subjects of litigation.","start":2283.113,"stop":2290.787,"duration":7.67}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that -- is the Commission an interest in that litigation?","start":2290.787,"stop":2295.669,"duration":4.88}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"No, we haven't -- we --","start":2295.669,"stop":2296.514,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Except the general -- the general interest in seeing that proper carriers are charged and faithful.","start":2296.514,"stop":2301.434,"duration":4.92}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Well -- well, they have -- they have two years.","start":2301.434,"stop":2304.657,"duration":3.22},{"text":"The railroads have two years for which they collect.","start":2304.657,"stop":2306.709,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2306.709,"stop":2309.991,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Those in the railroads decide they don't want to collect them, the Commission compel them?","start":2309.991,"stop":2319.686,"duration":9.7}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"It amount to a rebate.","start":2319.686,"stop":2320.69,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"A rebate.","start":2320.69,"stop":2321.087,"duration":0.4},{"text":"I -- I was going to say if it brings proceedings against them.","start":2321.087,"stop":2323.714,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"And willful rebating is a criminal violation of the Elkins Act.","start":2323.714,"stop":2327.18,"duration":3.47}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"To rebate to take in pursuant to the Commission's own order?","start":2327.18,"stop":2331.838,"duration":4.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Which -- which is --","start":2331.838,"stop":2333.001,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, but an order which was set aside (Voice Overlap) --","start":2333.001,"stop":2334.109,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":2334.109,"stop":2334.895,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"-- ab initio, an order which was set aside ab initio.","start":2334.895,"stop":2338.474,"duration":3.58}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, by the Court (Voice Overlap) --","start":2338.474,"stop":2339.162,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"This order had never been entered.","start":2339.162,"stop":2340.646,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The railroads acted under it and has it had to act under it so long as it -- it stood in effect.","start":2340.646,"stop":2345.945,"duration":5.3},{"text":"Do you think they can be prosecuted for that?","start":2345.945,"stop":2351.999,"duration":6.05}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"They could -- we could not prosecute them just forthwith but if -- if this judgment is sustained by this Court and -- and within a reasonable time, they do not undertake to -- to collect what would amount to undercharges under the judgment here before the Court, I suppose we'll have to look at the Elkins Act.","start":2351.999,"stop":2376.103,"duration":24.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Does the statute -- can you tell me this whether the statute for recovery by them -- all it does, actually, as to what time would that run and the time that -- that you fix the -- the proper rate?","start":2376.103,"stop":2390.52,"duration":14.42},{"text":"In other words, I -- I should think you're quite clear speaking for myself that if the railroad has a legal cause of action for rates collectible within two years when they fold their arms and waited and do nothing, that would be a clear violation of the Elkins Act, I should think.","start":2390.52,"stop":2408.551,"duration":18.03}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"At the same time, I would recommend to the Commission that -- that assuming this judgment were affirmed, I would recommend to the Commission to take no action until a railroad has had an opportunity to voluntarily to let themselves.","start":2408.551,"stop":2419.368,"duration":10.82}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, certainly.","start":2419.368,"stop":2422.422,"duration":3.05}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"But assuming reviewability, we still think that the Commission's order of vacating its prior suspension order should not have been set aside on the ground that it lacked findings.","start":2422.422,"stop":2436.783,"duration":14.36},{"text":"The suspension order of September 23 contained the statement which appears in the record at page 45 and at further appearing that upon consideration of the said schedules and protest thereto, there is reason to believe when the Commission didn't say \"We find that.\"","start":2436.783,"stop":2451.494,"duration":14.71},{"text":"There is reason to believe that they would if permitted to become effective result in rates and charges which would be unjust and unreasonable in violation of the Interstate Commerce Act and constitute unfair and destructive competitive practices in contravention of the National Transportation Policy.","start":2451.494,"stop":2474.942,"duration":23.45},{"text":"The later order of November 14, vacating the prior suspension order, contains the following statement which appears at page 47 of the record.","start":2474.942,"stop":2484.497,"duration":9.55},{"text":"It further appearing that consideration has been given to petitions of the respondents requesting vacation of the order suspension and to replies thereto and good cause appearing therefore.","start":2484.497,"stop":2498.376,"duration":13.88},{"text":"Now, the District Court based its conclusion on several -- on several factors.","start":2498.376,"stop":2504.544,"duration":6.17},{"text":"First, it said that the vacating order should have been accompanied by findings so as to facilitate judicial review, so that our reviewing court would understand the reasons for the Commission's action.","start":2504.544,"stop":2515.683,"duration":11.14},{"text":"But it's cited as authority for them, only a group of cases such as this Court's decision in Florida v. United States which stand for the proposition that such findings are required to support a final order made after the receipt of evidence in a hearing.","start":2515.683,"stop":2534.139,"duration":18.46},{"text":"No one of those cases relied upon by the District Court stands for the proposition that preliminary tentative orders such as these suspension actions must be accompanied by findings.","start":2534.139,"stop":2545.585,"duration":11.45},{"text":"And also as we contend that there is no -- there is no judicial review here to be facilitated by findings and -- and the conventional sense of the word.","start":2545.585,"stop":2555.83,"duration":10.24},{"text":"Secondly, the court below held that a requirement of findings was contained in Section 8 (b) of the Administrative Procedure Act, but the finding's requirements of Section 8 (b) of the Administrative Procedure Act applies only to orders issued after a hearing, a formal hearing which evidence is received.","start":2555.83,"stop":2574.429,"duration":18.6},{"text":"And this Court has specifically so held in the American Trucking case in 344 U.S.","start":2574.429,"stop":2581.117,"duration":6.69},{"text":"And since the Commission does not required to hold a hearing before it exercises its suspension powers, then it would seem that Section 8 (b) is finding new requirements can't possibly apply here.","start":2581.117,"stop":2591.465,"duration":10.35}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Ginnane, how were the parties made aware of the vacation of the original suspension order?","start":2591.465,"stop":2598.036,"duration":6.57},{"text":"Was that just a nice and taken by the Commission of which they were given some notice without any prior information that it was contemplated?","start":2598.036,"stop":2608.529,"duration":10.49}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, no.","start":2608.529,"stop":2610.099,"duration":1.57},{"text":"What happened after this -- the suspension order was issued on September 23, two weeks later in early November, the railroads filed petitions for reconsideration.","start":2610.099,"stop":2622.09,"duration":11.99},{"text":"Those petitions for reconsideration were served upon -- upon the motor carrier appellees --","start":2622.09,"stop":2626.911,"duration":4.82}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they (Voice Overlap) --","start":2626.911,"stop":2627.171,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and -- and they filed their replies.","start":2627.171,"stop":2629.652,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"They weren't argued to brief, were they?","start":2629.652,"stop":2631.52,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"No, there was no oral argument and no briefing in -- in this formal sense.","start":2631.52,"stop":2639.221,"duration":7.7},{"text":"There was petitions for the railroads for reconsideration and written replies by -- by the motor carriers.","start":2639.221,"stop":2645.102,"duration":5.88},{"text":"So, everybody concerned knew that reconsideration is a (Inaudible).","start":2645.102,"stop":2650.777,"duration":5.68},{"text":"Third, the District Court seem to view the statements and the Commission's original suspension order as being so definitive as being so (Inaudible) that it couldn't vacate that suspension order without giving in details, statement and reasons.","start":2650.777,"stop":2666.649,"duration":15.87},{"text":"For example, that -- referring to the suspension order of the District Court -- the District Court said that all parties were entitled to take this for its face value as a deliberate responsible articulate finding that the proposed rates would produce these illegal results.","start":2666.649,"stop":2682.306,"duration":15.66},{"text":"Well, of course, the Commission didn't make any such finding.","start":2682.306,"stop":2685.856,"duration":3.55},{"text":"He said, \"On consideration of the documents before us, there is reason to believe.\"","start":2685.856,"stop":2692.007,"duration":6.15},{"text":"Perhaps, it could be phrased as -- as a finding of probable cause on -- on the basis of speedy consideration.","start":2692.007,"stop":2700.459,"duration":8.45},{"text":"And note that Division 2 had one day, September 23, on which to decide whether to suspend the rates.","start":2700.459,"stop":2708.937,"duration":8.48},{"text":"And that one day and as addition to its original duty -- an addition to its other duties, it decides to suspend.","start":2708.937,"stop":2716.679,"duration":7.74},{"text":"It's on the basis of informal written presentation.","start":2716.679,"stop":2721.819,"duration":5.14},{"text":"These are not deliberate findings that most finding of probable cause.","start":2721.819,"stop":2729.376,"duration":7.56},{"text":"We submit that this -- that the rationale of the District Court overlooks that basic character of the whole suspension process.","start":2729.376,"stop":2737.855,"duration":8.48},{"text":"And turning to Section 15 (7) again, that requires the Commission when it suspends rates to state reasons to the carrier which initiated the rates and whether Commission refuses to suspend rates, it's not required to give reasons and customarily, it does not do so.","start":2737.855,"stop":2754.502,"duration":16.65},{"text":"And we submit that there's no practical difference between an original refusal to suspend and a later order vacating a prior suspension order because the net result is always the same that upon considering the available information and other limitations of time, ought means that the Commission in that is not sufficiently convinced that the rates are unlawful to interfere with the carrier statutory right to initiate rates subject to being set aside after a hearing.","start":2754.502,"stop":2792.114,"duration":37.61},{"text":"This power to suspend rates is a drastic administrative power.","start":2792.114,"stop":2799.237,"duration":7.12},{"text":"Its unwise exercise can impose heavy loses and upon either the initiating carrier or a competing carrier loses which they can in no way recruit.","start":2799.237,"stop":2810.036,"duration":10.8},{"text":"In considering the speed with which the suspension decisions must be made and on the limited informal record, a record untested by rebuttal, we urge that the Commission should be encourage to reconsider such decisions.","start":2810.036,"stop":2825.302,"duration":15.27},{"text":"And that such reconsideration on the basis of further deliberation should not be discouraged or made more difficult by attaching some sort of conclusion to the first -- some -- some form of conclusiveness to the initial decision which in this case had to be made within one day, September 23rd.","start":2825.302,"stop":2846.299,"duration":21},{"text":"And we contend --","start":2846.299,"stop":2846.705,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's what -- therefore, the test is with the -- with the suspension order.","start":2846.705,"stop":2850.449,"duration":3.74},{"text":"Can anybody come in and protest the suspension order in this case?","start":2850.449,"stop":2855.472,"duration":5.02}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, the -- the railroads had initiated the rates.","start":2855.472,"stop":2858.171,"duration":2.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2858.171,"stop":2858.604,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"They came piling and to protest the suspension order.","start":2858.604,"stop":2861.102,"duration":2.5},{"text":"But they -- they did that in the form of petition and for reconsideration.","start":2861.102,"stop":2864.035,"duration":2.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2864.035,"stop":2864.464,"duration":0.43},{"text":"But this -- is there in the record here -- and they didn't go to the Court to have -- as there been any -- as there been instances in which suspension orders by the Commission were contested in the proceedings for enjoinment as a good deal?","start":2864.464,"stop":2884.582,"duration":20.12}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"We've -- we've had one case also followed the instant case, The Universal Car Loading case in the Southern District of New York or a -- a carrier filed the complaint seeking review, the Commission order suspending the rate.","start":2884.582,"stop":2899.911,"duration":15.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean since 1910, the Commission must have been suspending thousands upon thousands of -- of carriers.","start":2899.911,"stop":2907.846,"duration":7.93},{"text":"And then --","start":2907.846,"stop":2908.116,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes about 2100 -- well, about 2000 a year.","start":2908.116,"stop":2912.062,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that evidently.","start":2912.062,"stop":2913.716,"duration":1.65},{"text":"Now, has the power to suspend on findings no more than this got into the courts at all during that hearing?","start":2913.716,"stop":2921.392,"duration":7.68}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"So far as we note, this is the first such case.","start":2921.392,"stop":2927.688,"duration":6.3},{"text":"Now, I'd like to call attention to a further practical danger of the decision below.","start":2927.688,"stop":2933.788,"duration":6.1},{"text":"As I suggested, these suspension actions are almost intuitive in character.","start":2933.788,"stop":2940.394,"duration":6.61},{"text":"They are made rapidly by rate experts but upon incomplete when sometimes incomplete and always informal records.","start":2940.394,"stop":2949.666,"duration":9.27},{"text":"To the extent that under the decision below, the Commission in deciding whether to suspend or not to suspend or whether to vacate a prior suspension order is required to make detail findings and various elements which go into the lawfulness of rates.","start":2949.666,"stop":2965.619,"duration":15.95},{"text":"It may be forced into unconscious prejudgment, officials going into the lawfulness of rates which I think everyone would agree, it should finally decide only after a hearing in which evidence is received.","start":2965.619,"stop":2982.718,"duration":17.1},{"text":"My colleague, Mr. McDowell can take the rest of the time.","start":2982.718,"stop":2990.866,"duration":8.15}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. McDowell.","start":2990.866,"stop":2993.182,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":2993.182,"stop":2994.538,"duration":1.36},{"text":"I would like to develop briefly with the time alloted some of the questions that might be involved on the mootness issue which Mr. Justice Harlan raised and Mr. Justice Frankfurter has discussed.","start":2994.538,"stop":3011.768,"duration":17.23},{"text":"I think the best way to -- to follow this mootness question is to follow the chronology of the case.","start":3011.768,"stop":3020.302,"duration":8.53},{"text":"The contention of these appellee seemed to be that the question of mootness arises out of the fact that since the suspension order of September the 23rd, 1955 expired by its own terms.","start":3020.302,"stop":3035.178,"duration":14.88},{"text":"On April the 23rd, 1956, some seven months later, that the entire matter then came to a rest and there is nothing further to be decided or there is now not left any justiciable controversy to the exploration of this -- this order.","start":3035.178,"stop":3055.338,"duration":20.16},{"text":"Now, I think that the situation can best be illustrated like this.","start":3055.338,"stop":3063.061,"duration":7.72},{"text":"Following the vacation of the suspension by the Commission on November the 14th, effective as of November the 24th, the rail carriers filed a supplement putting in these reduced rates and they became effective on November the 24th and they were affected -- effective for nine weeks that is until the Court set them aside in their judgment of January the 24th.","start":3063.061,"stop":3095.501,"duration":32.44},{"text":"Now, when the Court set them aside on January the 24th, it did not say \"Cancel these rates as of this moment.","start":3095.501,"stop":3104.274,"duration":8.77},{"text":"Leave the rates that were in effect for this intervening nine weeks period in effect.\"","start":3104.274,"stop":3109.084,"duration":4.81},{"text":"They said, \"No.","start":3109.084,"stop":3111.06,"duration":1.98},{"text":"Go back now to November the 24th and the rates that were in effect at that time should have been in effect all during these nine weeks period.\"","start":3111.06,"stop":3122.461,"duration":11.4},{"text":"The consequence of that, insofar as the railroads are concern, is that we have undercharged the shippers.","start":3122.461,"stop":3131.181,"duration":8.72},{"text":"Since we charged them a lower basis of rate for that nine-week period, then the Court said we should have charged them.","start":3131.181,"stop":3137.848,"duration":6.67},{"text":"Now then, we have got the obligation under the Elkins Act to collect those undercharges if the lower court's decision is correct because a carrier cannot charge any shipper anything other than the published rate.","start":3137.848,"stop":3154.445,"duration":16.6},{"text":"And since the Court says that the only rate that was published in this case was the rates that were in effect prior to the vacation of the suspension.","start":3154.445,"stop":3163.602,"duration":9.16},{"text":"Now, going on one step further, that's the railroad's position.","start":3163.602,"stop":3168.625,"duration":5.02},{"text":"Beginning on January the 24th, the date of the judgment of the trial court in which they said, \"Now, go back to November the 24th and put all these -- all rates back into existence.","start":3168.625,"stop":3179.575,"duration":10.95},{"text":"That's the way the situation should be.\"","start":3179.575,"stop":3182.209,"duration":2.63},{"text":"Then beginning from that time forward, the shippers and carriers have the question as to whether or not from January 24th to the exploration suspension order whether or not they were overcharged because you see the Court has reinstituted the higher rates or reestablished the higher rates that were in existence as of that date.","start":3182.209,"stop":3205.436,"duration":23.23},{"text":"So they have got three months, so what they view as overcharges by the carrier.","start":3205.436,"stop":3211.875,"duration":6.44},{"text":"Now then, with those two issues in the matter, it is not a moot controversy.","start":3211.875,"stop":3217.109,"duration":5.23},{"text":"There is something to be decided here and it's a very same consideration.","start":3217.109,"stop":3221.713,"duration":4.6},{"text":"Those considerations, the very same consideration, that this Court took into consideration in the Southern Pacific case and the -- which is not cited in the appellee's brief and in Southern Pacific Company against ICC at 219 U.S., 433.","start":3221.713,"stop":3242.081,"duration":20.37},{"text":"Now, they cited --","start":3242.081,"stop":3242.238,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":3242.238,"stop":3242.842,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"-- a case called the Southern Pacific Terminal Company case decided on the same day by this Court but they did not cite the Southern Pacific Company against the ICC 219.","start":3242.842,"stop":3255.514,"duration":12.67},{"text":"Now in that case, the Court said -- this Court said, the contention of mootness is disposed off by the Southern Pacific Terminal Company case.","start":3255.514,"stop":3265.565,"duration":10.05},{"text":"This, they decide.","start":3265.565,"stop":3267.17,"duration":1.61},{"text":"They went on -- this Court went on to say in addition to the considerations expressed in that case, it is to be observed that clearly the suggestion of mootness is without merit in view of the possible liability of reparations to which the railroads might be subjected if the legality of the order were not determined.","start":3267.17,"stop":3287.784,"duration":20.61}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"Did everybody agree that after April 26, it's beyond the fact?Is that all settled?","start":3287.784,"stop":3295.099,"duration":7.32},{"text":"That after April 26, that -- that there is no -- no basis for attacking the reduced rates to the --","start":3295.099,"stop":3302.806,"duration":7.71}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3302.806,"stop":3303.561,"duration":0.76},{"text":"No sir, not in the basis for attacking the reduced rates because the Commission entered upon a formal investigation of these rates --","start":3303.561,"stop":3310.458,"duration":6.9}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":3310.458,"stop":3310.861,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and upheld hearings.","start":3310.861,"stop":3311.852,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"In the motor carriers, don't -- they don't claim any right to attack that act after April 26?","start":3311.852,"stop":3316.349,"duration":4.5}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"That is not involved here.","start":3316.349,"stop":3317.596,"duration":1.25},{"text":"I assume they could claim the right to do it but the petition for reconsideration on that investigation by the Commission was denied in November -- on November the 19th, 1956 and they haven't seen fit to attack it yet.","start":3317.596,"stop":3334.353,"duration":16.76},{"text":"But I don't say that I don't assume that they would say they don't have the right even yet may be.","start":3334.353,"stop":3339.022,"duration":4.67},{"text":"Maybe latches would catch them.","start":3339.022,"stop":3340.268,"duration":1.25},{"text":"I don't know.","start":3340.268,"stop":3343.006,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"If they have a right because you -- you have -- have a live matter to decide.","start":3343.006,"stop":3348.36,"duration":5.35}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, certainly, sir.","start":3348.36,"stop":3349.548,"duration":1.19},{"text":"We think we have a live matter to decide because we are -- as I said, the railroads are placed with undercharges for nine weeks and the duty of collecting, if the lower court's opinion is correct.","start":3349.548,"stop":3363.216,"duration":13.67},{"text":"The shippers and the carriers on the other hand are faced with overcharges for a period of three months, if the lower court's decision is incorrect.","start":3363.216,"stop":3376.375,"duration":13.16},{"text":"Now then --","start":3376.375,"stop":3379.316,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course, there's another way of dealing with the matter, Mr. McDowell.","start":3379.316,"stop":3382.903,"duration":3.59},{"text":"If -- if this Court finds -- I'm not saying that your line of reasoning as modern force has validity, but if this Court should find that the appeal was moot -- rendered moot by the null finding of the Commission, it would then -- if it vacated that -- what the law -- the District Court did wipe it off the books, then you wouldn't be under this restriction of not collecting an undercharge -- an improper undercharge.","start":3382.903,"stop":3419.828,"duration":36.93}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's true, sir.","start":3419.828,"stop":3421.045,"duration":1.22},{"text":"If the Court would vacate what the lower court has done in order to set the record straight, it would not --","start":3421.045,"stop":3428.859,"duration":7.81}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It wouldn't adverse the effect.","start":3428.859,"stop":3430.358,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"But we would be back sometime later with the same problem again because this is a continuing proposition that the --","start":3430.358,"stop":3436.642,"duration":6.28}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And the same problem of whether --","start":3436.642,"stop":3439.174,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"Whether the order of the Commission was reviewable and whether it has to be supported by fact.","start":3439.174,"stop":3442.88,"duration":3.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In fact -- a fact that a case may -- that a question may turn up here again is not a good reason for --","start":3442.88,"stop":3449.237,"duration":6.36}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I understand.","start":3449.237,"stop":3449.627,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- yet if the question isn't properly here.","start":3449.627,"stop":3451.802,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that.","start":3451.802,"stop":3452.846,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I know that's -- that bothers counselor (Inaudible) I'm trying to find.","start":3452.846,"stop":3458.64,"duration":5.79}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"Now then, if I might go on in limited time, there is -- the further point in this case of the Court intruding into the rate making function, the lower court's intrusion into that function by setting aside rates which were lawfully in effect and reestablishing rates which had been cancelled.","start":3458.64,"stop":3486.817,"duration":28.18},{"text":"Now, I briefly touch on it.","start":3486.817,"stop":3493.853,"duration":7.04},{"text":"As we pointed out, the challenged order of November 14th vacated the suspension as of November 24th.","start":3493.853,"stop":3502.588,"duration":8.74},{"text":"On that day, these reduced rates went into effect and were in effect until voided by lower court's opinion in January.","start":3502.588,"stop":3511.686,"duration":9.1},{"text":"In the complaint filed in this case by the appellees, we find this statement, once a schedule becomes effective, there is considerable doubt whether even a subsequent setting aside of the Commission's order could in law have the effect of cancelling the schedules in effect.","start":3511.686,"stop":3532.195,"duration":20.51},{"text":"Now, we have agreed with that contention ever since we have been proceeding in this case.","start":3532.195,"stop":3537.09,"duration":4.89},{"text":"We think that is a sound contention.","start":3537.09,"stop":3539.249,"duration":2.16},{"text":"It is a contention that was raised by the appellees in order to prevail upon the lower court to grant him a temporary restraining order which he denied.","start":3539.249,"stop":3548.91,"duration":9.66},{"text":"The Commission's power to set aside rates, which is touched on by Mr. Ginnane which are already in effect, is limited by these restrictions of Section 15 including the requirements of a full hearing.","start":3548.91,"stop":3564.277,"duration":15.37},{"text":"Now, to compel, as this lower court would do, the Commission to take such action without a full hearing would be to telling the Commission to disregard their statutory limitations and proceed as the Court direct.","start":3564.277,"stop":3578.2,"duration":13.92},{"text":"Now then, the grant of power to the Commission to suspend rates prior to their effective date was itself innovation or radical departure by the Mann-Elkins Act.","start":3578.2,"stop":3589.963,"duration":11.76},{"text":"It represented as Mr. Ginnane has already stated an exception to this traditional right of the carriers to initiate their -- all rates.","start":3589.963,"stop":3598.081,"duration":8.12},{"text":"But the effect of this lower court's decision is to suspend rates after they have gone into effect but prior to a full hearing which the Commission is not even empowered by the Act to do.","start":3598.081,"stop":3611.969,"duration":13.89},{"text":"If the Commission's orders, when it gets into a question of reasonableness of rates, other than on the reparation issue, they do not cancel rates retroactively.","start":3611.969,"stop":3623.157,"duration":11.19},{"text":"They order them cancel if they find them unreasonable and unjust prospectively but not retroactively.","start":3623.157,"stop":3631.105,"duration":7.95},{"text":"But this Court has gone one step further and ordered them cancelled retroactively before April hearing.","start":3631.105,"stop":3638.008,"duration":6.9},{"text":"Now, when they get into a situation of that nature, they are actually in the field of rate making because they are establishing rates which the Commission has not established, which the carriers have not established and they are actually putting those rates into the book entirely contrary to any authority even resting with the Interstate Commerce Commission.","start":3638.008,"stop":3666.017,"duration":28.01},{"text":"I believe that my time is up.","start":3666.017,"stop":3668.494,"duration":2.48},{"text":"We submit --","start":3668.494,"stop":3669.44,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"How had the rates been fixed that you suspend that you cut down and produced?","start":3669.44,"stop":3675.09,"duration":5.65}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"How had they had been fixed?","start":3675.09,"stop":3675.982,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, how had they originally had been fixed?","start":3675.982,"stop":3678.312,"duration":2.33}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"They had been fixed by the publication of tariff under Section 6 (3) of the Interstate Commerce Act published on statutory notice and allowed to go into effect because they were not suspended by the Interstate Commerce Commission.","start":3678.312,"stop":3689.486,"duration":11.17}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Had they ever been challenged?","start":3689.486,"stop":3691.989,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.As far as I know, the rates that were in effect prior to this reduction had not been challenged.","start":3691.989,"stop":3697.792,"duration":5.8}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"How long --","start":3697.792,"stop":3697.906,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"There may have been a request for a protest filed against them but it wasn't successful.","start":3697.906,"stop":3702.58,"duration":4.67},{"text":"Now, I don't --","start":3702.58,"stop":3703.014,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"How long had they been in effect?","start":3703.014,"stop":3705.18,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"They had been in effect since the early report on 1954.","start":3705.18,"stop":3710.797,"duration":5.62}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"This is a typical case that the carriers are trying to meet modal competition.","start":3710.797,"stop":3716.688,"duration":5.89}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"Actually, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, it is not.","start":3716.688,"stop":3720.178,"duration":3.49},{"text":"The -- the motivating factor behind this case was large competition.","start":3720.178,"stop":3726.29,"duration":6.11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Barge company holds --","start":3726.29,"stop":3726.998,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"The United States -- Rubber Company had developed a rubber container for the shipping of carbon black.","start":3726.998,"stop":3733.026,"duration":6.03}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, any -- anyhow, there's a competition of a rival carrier and -- and the reduction of rate under the -- under the 1920 Act.","start":3733.026,"stop":3741.121,"duration":8.1}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, sir.","start":3741.121,"stop":3741.503,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what they say.","start":3741.503,"stop":3742.44,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Did they have the same power you do?","start":3742.44,"stop":3745.929,"duration":3.49},{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":3745.929,"stop":3746.034,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"To initiate rates, sir?","start":3746.034,"stop":3747.839,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Did -- did they have the same power you do to reduce your rates than --","start":3747.839,"stop":3752.578,"duration":4.74}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3752.578,"stop":3752.974,"duration":0.4},{"text":"They have the same power we do, of course, subject to the control of the regulatory agency.","start":3752.974,"stop":3757.685,"duration":4.71}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, subject to the --","start":3757.685,"stop":3758.289,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"But --","start":3758.289,"stop":3758.484,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- same control here if they had put their rates in effect.","start":3758.484,"stop":3763.386,"duration":4.9}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"You're speaking with the boards line, sir?","start":3763.386,"stop":3765.07,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, or whoever is you're competing with.","start":3765.07,"stop":3767.278,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3767.278,"stop":3767.861,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They have to increase them, wouldn't they?","start":3767.861,"stop":3769.292,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, they would -- they might --","start":3769.292,"stop":3772.063,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"We have the same proceeding before the ICC if that's what you mean.","start":3772.063,"stop":3777.15,"duration":5.09}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Or was it -- there is something about $1.53 rate being frozen and I recalled something like that in the (Voice Overlap) --","start":3777.15,"stop":3782.413,"duration":5.26}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3782.413,"stop":3782.771,"duration":0.36},{"text":"I wish I had time to develop it for you and if you bear with me, that illustrates the inappropriateness of a trial court getting into these matters.","start":3782.771,"stop":3793.842,"duration":11.07},{"text":"The truck line rates had been suspended by the Commission but involved in that case was whether or not they were compensatory which is the first test of a rate, involved in that case were certain other factors.","start":3793.842,"stop":3807.079,"duration":13.24},{"text":"What the truck lines would -- been doing was trying to establish on a 28,000 pound minimum, the same level of rates that the railroads published on a 65,000 pound minimum.","start":3807.079,"stop":3820.468,"duration":13.39},{"text":"And those were factors and considerations which the Commission had first been confronted with and they wanted the right to look at.","start":3820.468,"stop":3828.553,"duration":8.09}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, do I understand that (Voice Overlap) --","start":3828.553,"stop":3828.961,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, the factors were entirely different between the railroad case and the motor carrier case.","start":3828.961,"stop":3833.819,"duration":4.86}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, but do I correctly understand that the motor carriers must charge at a rate not less then $1.53 100 weight whereas the new rail rates are $1.33?","start":3833.819,"stop":3844.593,"duration":10.77}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, since that time, their motor carriers have reduced their rates and I think the figure you are mentioning is from an origin in the Panhandle Texas to Akron, Ohio and I believe their rates on 100 pounds is 1.4785 and ours is now 1.33.","start":3844.593,"stop":3859.934,"duration":15.34}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":3859.934,"stop":3862.07,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"Again --","start":3862.07,"stop":3862.655,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Did they try --","start":3862.655,"stop":3863.039,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Justice --","start":3863.039,"stop":3863.765,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- did they try to reduce that or change that?","start":3863.765,"stop":3868.462,"duration":4.7}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"They have.","start":3868.462,"stop":3869.606,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That at -- after you made your change, did they try to change that?","start":3869.606,"stop":3872.432,"duration":2.83}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"They had a change pending at the time we made our change.","start":3872.432,"stop":3875.62,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Did this Commission grant them the right to change --","start":3875.62,"stop":3877.7,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"After a full investigation, yes, sir.","start":3877.7,"stop":3882.352,"duration":4.65},{"text":"It was effective on December the 14th I believe --","start":3882.352,"stop":3885.592,"duration":3.24}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But what about --","start":3885.592,"stop":3885.798,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"-- just two days after the hearing in this case.","start":3885.798,"stop":3887.514,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What about the suspension?","start":3887.514,"stop":3889.562,"duration":2.05},{"text":"Did the --","start":3889.562,"stop":3889.954,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"They did -- they suspended their rates on our protest.","start":3889.954,"stop":3892.776,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Who did?","start":3892.776,"stop":3894.003,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"The ICC --","start":3894.003,"stop":3895.111,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The ICC.","start":3895.111,"stop":3895.633,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"-- back in 1954 because as I mentioned to him, there were certain factors and considerations which we call to their attention and they ordered the right to look at it.","start":3895.633,"stop":3905.473,"duration":9.84},{"text":"They involved making rates on much lower minimums than the real carriers that made these rates applicable.","start":3905.473,"stop":3910.562,"duration":5.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"How long did that suspension lies until they made a determination on validity of the rates would be down?","start":3910.562,"stop":3915.86,"duration":5.3}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it lasted, of course, for seven months under -- under --","start":3915.86,"stop":3918.784,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3918.784,"stop":3918.89,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the Act but it was voluntarily extended until December --","start":3918.89,"stop":3922.558,"duration":3.67}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't mean your rate.","start":3922.558,"stop":3923.592,"duration":1.03},{"text":"I mean the one that -- that you (Voice Overlap) --","start":3923.592,"stop":3924.827,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm talking about the motor carrier.","start":3924.827,"stop":3928.317,"duration":3.49},{"text":"I don't know the beginning date but the Commission finally decided the case, that is the reasonableness of this case, on December the 14th, 1955.","start":3928.317,"stop":3938.543,"duration":10.23},{"text":"Now, I think they had been suspended since -- probably around April or May of 1954.","start":3938.543,"stop":3947.478,"duration":8.93},{"text":"And please don't --","start":3947.478,"stop":3948.5,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand.","start":3948.5,"stop":3949.119,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"-- hang me on that particular date around in that time.","start":3949.119,"stop":3950.238,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm just trying to see -- that's the kind of a time spent that is normal in this situation, isn't Mr. McDowell?","start":3950.238,"stop":3957.803,"duration":7.57}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"If the rate is once suspended, yes.","start":3957.803,"stop":3959.389,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean that's the kind of a normal time before it gets around to determination on the reasonableness.","start":3959.389,"stop":3964.296,"duration":4.91}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"It could be when there are innovations.","start":3964.296,"stop":3967.302,"duration":3.01}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3967.302,"stop":3967.756,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"I'll put it that way, if it's not.","start":3967.756,"stop":3969.265,"duration":1.51},{"text":"If there are no innovations in the case, then they can decide it much faster.","start":3969.265,"stop":3973.002,"duration":3.74}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What were the rate relationships during that period of time due to the two orders of the Commission?","start":3973.002,"stop":3979.199,"duration":6.2},{"text":"Will you let the charge more or less --","start":3979.199,"stop":3982.255,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, beginning in 1954 as the appellee's brief will show, using again this representative rate from Texas Panhandle to Akron, Ohio, their rates were 3 cents lower than our in 1954.","start":3982.255,"stop":3996.736,"duration":14.48},{"text":"Beginning in 1954, we put a rate in of $1.4785 which made our rate 5.15 cents lower than theirs.","start":3996.736,"stop":4006.412,"duration":9.68}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that the one that was dissented?","start":4006.412,"stop":4007.954,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":4007.954,"stop":4008.672,"duration":0.72},{"text":"Then we came along in order to meet some barge competition put in a rate of 133 per 100 pounds for that the same representative origin or destination.","start":4008.672,"stop":4016.135,"duration":7.46}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What were the barge rates at that time?","start":4016.135,"stop":4018.093,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":4018.093,"stop":4018.655,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What were the barge rates at that time?","start":4018.655,"stop":4020.179,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"They were much lower than that, sir, on -- on 100 pound basis -- on a 100 pound basis from the areas around the Mississippi up to --","start":4020.179,"stop":4027.944,"duration":7.76}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm trying to find out just what's the cause of this argument here in relationship with the rates used the Commission's order?","start":4027.944,"stop":4036.735,"duration":8.79},{"text":"Did you get an advantage or the other side gets an advantage?","start":4036.735,"stop":4039.209,"duration":2.47},{"text":"What does it claim?","start":4039.209,"stop":4039.912,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"[Laughs].","start":4039.912,"stop":4041.137,"duration":1.23},{"text":"He claims we got an advantage, sir.","start":4041.137,"stop":4043.069,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Because you --","start":4043.069,"stop":4043.458,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"Because --","start":4043.458,"stop":4043.827,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- you cut down --","start":4043.827,"stop":4044.17,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"-- his rates were suspended and ours weren't.","start":4044.17,"stop":4045.945,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"No, you -- would that leave you free to cut under him, under them?","start":4045.945,"stop":4050.252,"duration":4.31}]},{"speakerName":"William R. McDowell","textObjs":[{"text":"Not any further.","start":4050.252,"stop":4051.163,"duration":0.91},{"text":"The only rate was -- the rates were involved were the ones that were not suspended.","start":4051.163,"stop":4054.419,"duration":3.26},{"text":"In other words, we didn't go back and asked to put in another scale of rates to cut further.","start":4054.419,"stop":4059.062,"duration":4.64},{"text":"But he says, his were suspended and ours weren't and we have the advantage during this interim.","start":4059.062,"stop":4067.397,"duration":8.34}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess.","start":4067.397,"stop":4075.111,"duration":7.71}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - March 05, 1957","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren5/oral_argument_audio/13323","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Arkansas & Louisiana Missouri Railway Company et al., versus Amarillo-Borger Express Incorporated et al., and Number 224, United States of America versus Amarillo-Borger Express.","start":0,"stop":15.85,"duration":15.85},{"text":"Mr. Currie, you may proceed.","start":15.85,"stop":24.55,"duration":8.7}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and -- may it please the Court.","start":24.55,"stop":32.7,"duration":8.15},{"text":"Within the time which is allotted to me, I want to discuss the several legal questions that are presented by this appeal, including the question of mootness, and thereafter, assuming that a justiciable controversy exist my reasons for arguing that the judgment of the court below should be affirmed.","start":32.7,"stop":62.281,"duration":29.58},{"text":"But before I begin the legal argument, I think it's appropriate and I believe I can be of the greatest assistance to the Court if I recite what the facts are, because it is difficult for me to explain my reasons for a legal conclusion without associating it with the facts upon which these conclusions are based.","start":62.281,"stop":95.356,"duration":33.07},{"text":"Now, the commodity that we're dealing with here is a commodity known as carbon black.","start":95.356,"stop":102.771,"duration":7.42},{"text":"Carbon black is a product of natural gas and oil.","start":102.771,"stop":107.654,"duration":4.88},{"text":"It is produced primarily in the State of Texas and -- in the Southwest.","start":107.654,"stop":113.897,"duration":6.24},{"text":"And the Panhandle area of Texas is the largest producer of carbon black.","start":113.897,"stop":121.058,"duration":7.16},{"text":"The principal users of carbon black are the rubber manufacturers or the tire manufacturers.","start":121.058,"stop":129.445,"duration":8.39},{"text":"The -- there's a statement in the record to the effect that approximately 95% of all carbon black is used in the manufacture of rubber to its entirety.","start":129.445,"stop":144.279,"duration":14.83},{"text":"The Interstate Commerce Commission found in this particular proceeding and -- and the proceedings reported in 298 I.C.C. at 721.","start":144.279,"stop":153.929,"duration":9.65},{"text":"And on page 723 of that decision, the Interstate Commerce Commission in this case pointed out that between 40% and 60% of all of the carbon black that was used in rubber was consumed around the Akron, Ohio area.","start":153.929,"stop":174.442,"duration":20.51},{"text":"So that for all practical purposes what we have here was a movement, a tremendous movement of carbon black from the Panhandle area of Texas into Akron, Ohio.","start":174.442,"stop":188.929,"duration":14.49},{"text":"The Commission's proceeding also discussed the fact that during the years 1954 and 1955, there seemed to be about 700,000 tons of this commodity that moved.","start":188.929,"stop":203.176,"duration":14.25},{"text":"It's quite a substantial movement.","start":203.176,"stop":205.703,"duration":2.53},{"text":"And the figures revealed to the Commission and recited by it in that decision.","start":205.703,"stop":213.352,"duration":7.65},{"text":"It showed that 66 and ninth-tenth percent of it was moved by rail during those years and 28 -- eighth -- and eight-tenth percent by motor carrier with four and three-tenths percent by seatrain.","start":213.352,"stop":227.091,"duration":13.74},{"text":"A seatrain is a water carrier that holds loaded railroad cars.","start":227.091,"stop":231.536,"duration":4.44},{"text":"There was no movement by barge and by way of momentary digression, it is hard for me to restrain a chuckle when I hear counsel say as he did yesterday that the purpose in reducing these rate was to forestall barge competition because there immediately appears before my mind the picture of a barge moving from the area Panhandle of Texas across the plains there to Akron, Ohio which is also a place not on water.","start":231.536,"stop":267.756,"duration":36.22},{"text":"The truth is that this movement of carbon black, it moved entirely by rail or by motor carrier.","start":267.756,"stop":276.549,"duration":8.79},{"text":"Those were the two competing forms of transportation that moved it.","start":276.549,"stop":281.296,"duration":4.75},{"text":"Now, prior to 1954, and I will let you say this.","start":281.296,"stop":288.117,"duration":6.82},{"text":"It constituted for the appellees and motor carriers whom I represent here a very important piece of business.","start":288.117,"stop":297.779,"duration":9.66},{"text":"It was important out of proportion to the revenue we received for it because it supplied us with a return haul.","start":297.779,"stop":307.504,"duration":9.73},{"text":"You see, under our certificates which the Commission issued to us, we are not allowed to handle products in bulk.","start":307.504,"stop":316.414,"duration":8.91},{"text":"We are not allowed to handle livestock.","start":316.414,"stop":320.624,"duration":4.21},{"text":"Now, in the Panhandle area of Texas, the things that are produced are grain, which moves in bulk and oil which moves in bulk or by pipeline and carriers.","start":320.624,"stop":333.148,"duration":12.52},{"text":"Consequently, when we carry products of general merchandise into the West Texas Panhandle area, there is little that we are authorized to move back.","start":333.148,"stop":346.547,"duration":13.4},{"text":"And carbon black which moves in sacks is a commodity which offered us a return haul into the Akron, Ohio area.","start":346.547,"stop":356.765,"duration":10.22},{"text":"So, it was of a -- a great deal of importance and at the time this controversy arose.","start":356.765,"stop":363.623,"duration":6.86},{"text":"We were -- excuse me.","start":363.623,"stop":366.865,"duration":3.24},{"text":"We were getting revenues in excess of a $1000 a day out of this transportation of the small percentage of the carbon black that we were being privileged to handle.","start":366.865,"stop":381.172,"duration":14.31},{"text":"Prior to 1954, the rail rates and the motor carrier rates were on the same level or substantially the same level.","start":381.172,"stop":390.654,"duration":9.48},{"text":"It had been that way for some time.","start":390.654,"stop":393.104,"duration":2.45},{"text":"Now, during the period following World War II, there had been blanket general increases granted to the railroads and taken by the motor carriers.","start":393.104,"stop":405.247,"duration":12.14},{"text":"And as a result of this -- of the application of these blanket general increases, the rates got slightly out of adjustment.","start":405.247,"stop":412.18,"duration":6.93},{"text":"The typical illustration which everybody agrees was typical, was the rate from the Panhandle points of Texas such as Borger and Amarillo into Akron, Ohio.","start":412.18,"stop":427.529,"duration":15.35},{"text":"There, the -- the rate when you add it on the various increases and calculated them according to the different formulas, the rails had a rate of $1.56 a hundred and the motor carriers a rate of $1.53 a hundred.","start":427.529,"stop":444.631,"duration":17.1},{"text":"The railroads in -- early in 1954 filed a new schedule and reduced their rate not to meet the motor carrier rate but down to $1.4785, one hundredths cents per hundred, which put them five and fifteen one hundred cents per hundred pounds below the then prevailing motor carrier rate.","start":444.631,"stop":473.741,"duration":29.11},{"text":"The motor carriers then filed with the Commission a new tariff seeking to establish the same $1.4785 per hundred pounds.","start":473.741,"stop":485.179,"duration":11.44},{"text":"The rails protested that and the Commission suspended the rates of the motor carrier.","start":485.179,"stop":493.404,"duration":8.23},{"text":"That was in 1954.","start":493.404,"stop":496.122,"duration":2.72},{"text":"Hearing was had on the suspension.","start":496.122,"stop":498.167,"duration":2.04},{"text":"They entered onto an investigation and the hearing was had in July 1954.","start":498.167,"stop":503.768,"duration":5.6},{"text":"The seven months period expired with no action on the part of the Commission and the motor carriers voluntarily extended the period of suspension and this was the customary practice we are told until the Commission could complete its investigation.","start":503.768,"stop":523.961,"duration":20.19},{"text":"At the time of the controversy which had its inception in September 1925 -- of 1955, the Commission had not yet completed its investigation and had not handed down its decision.","start":523.961,"stop":540.736,"duration":16.77},{"text":"Neither had it done so at the time of the trial in the court below.","start":540.736,"stop":546.214,"duration":5.48},{"text":"So that the practical effect of that situation was that the railroads were enjoying a differential of five and fifteen-one hundred cents below our rate, notwithstanding that differential in their favor.","start":546.214,"stop":563.231,"duration":17.02},{"text":"They proceeded by carriers which were scheduled to become effective on September the 24th, 1955.","start":563.231,"stop":573.548,"duration":10.32},{"text":"Rates which cut the particular rate down from a dollar forty-seven eighty-five down to a dollar thirty-three, precisely twenty cents, a hundred pounds under our rate.","start":573.548,"stop":587.569,"duration":14.02},{"text":"We knew then that we could not exist with a twenty-cent differential against this.Even the 28% of the traffic we were getting would be gone with 700,000 tons moving that.","start":587.569,"stop":603.822,"duration":16.25},{"text":"20 cents a hundred is -- is quite a difference.","start":603.822,"stop":607.575,"duration":3.75},{"text":"So, we petitioned the Interstate Commerce Commission to suspend those rates on the ground as we thought that they were -- the rail carriers were embarking upon a course of a destructive competitive practice that was in contravention on the National Transportation Policy.","start":607.575,"stop":633.069,"duration":25.49},{"text":"The -- the Commission suspended our rates, I mean the rail rates.","start":633.069,"stop":638.72,"duration":5.65},{"text":"Our petition was granted.","start":638.72,"stop":641.973,"duration":3.25},{"text":"By its order of September the 23rd, 1955 the Interstate Commerce Commission, not the Board of Suspension, but the Commission, the Division 2 itself, acting as an appellate division entered this order which was admitted by everybody to be a valid order and well within the powers of the Commission.","start":641.973,"stop":660.354,"duration":18.38}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did it go through the Board of Suspension?","start":660.354,"stop":662.21,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"It did, sir, yes.","start":662.21,"stop":663.051,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And they just -- they just channeled it over the -- to them?","start":663.051,"stop":665.649,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":665.649,"stop":666.127,"duration":0.48},{"text":"They -- well, we had a conference and the record reveals this sentence.","start":666.127,"stop":670.063,"duration":3.94},{"text":"We had a conference and the Board of Suspension which is the -- the employees of the Commission declined to suspend.","start":670.063,"stop":679.253,"duration":9.19},{"text":"And immediately, we asked the -- the Division itself to look into the matter and on the same day, the Commission did look into it and decided the Board was wrong and issued this order suspending the rates.","start":679.253,"stop":692.097,"duration":12.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose they -- supposed they have concluded that the Board of Suspension were right, could they -- in the same quick manner sustain the Board and just said the order of suspension or Board of Suspension approve -- or Board of Suspension approved herein?","start":692.097,"stop":716.515,"duration":24.42}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":716.515,"stop":717.027,"duration":0.51},{"text":"I -- I don't know what they would have had to say.","start":717.027,"stop":719.212,"duration":2.18},{"text":"Probably, they would have had to say nothing.","start":719.212,"stop":720.815,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But suppose they said nothing, that was my question, would they have to say anything?","start":720.815,"stop":725.466,"duration":4.65}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"If they didn't want to reverse the Board of Suspension, they wouldn't have to say anything.","start":725.466,"stop":728.839,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's say approved on a piece of paper that came up to it, is that right?","start":728.839,"stop":733.44,"duration":4.6}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, sir.","start":733.44,"stop":734.565,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In those findings, why they didn't suspend?","start":734.565,"stop":737.913,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir, and the reason for that is this, Mr. Justice Frankfurter.","start":737.913,"stop":743.131,"duration":5.22},{"text":"And I'll digress from the statement of facts for the moment to say this.","start":743.131,"stop":745.357,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Don't -- don't follow my irrelevance.","start":745.357,"stop":748.098,"duration":2.74},{"text":"You stick to your proper argument.","start":748.098,"stop":750.638,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"But I would like to answer your question, sir.","start":750.638,"stop":752.83,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, do it.","start":752.83,"stop":753.233,"duration":0.4},{"text":"It's relevant, not otherwise.","start":753.233,"stop":755.61,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it -- it's relevant.","start":755.61,"stop":756.868,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":756.868,"stop":758.033,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly.","start":758.033,"stop":760.08,"duration":2.05},{"text":"You see, the carrier under the statute -- under Section 15 subsection 7 of the Interstate Commerce Act.","start":760.08,"stop":767.227,"duration":7.15},{"text":"The carrier has the right to initiate its own rates, simply by publishing them with the Commission and as -- given 30 days notice.","start":767.227,"stop":777.287,"duration":10.06},{"text":"At the exploration of the 30-day period, the rates go into effect unless the Commission by affirmative action has stopped them from going into effect.","start":777.287,"stop":787.055,"duration":9.77},{"text":"So that if the Commission decides that it is not going to suspend, all it needs do is nothing and the rates go into effect.","start":787.055,"stop":796.366,"duration":9.31},{"text":"It requires affirmative action on the part of the Commission to make a -- a rate that the carrier has a right to initiate -- suspend it and you operate it.","start":796.366,"stop":807.782,"duration":11.42}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So that this -- this -- from your point of view slashing ruthless tariff, proposed tariff by the -- filed tariff by the railroads would have gone into effect with all the evil consequences that you've laid before us, is that right?","start":807.782,"stop":823.312,"duration":15.53}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Except for the action of the Commission, except for the action of the Interstate Commerce Commission which on the -- on September the 23rd, 1955 issued its order finding this probable unlawfulness and suspending the record.","start":823.312,"stop":841.071,"duration":17.76}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm assuming the contrary hypothesis that the Board of Suspension rejected your protest or at least didn't act on it favorably, acted on it unfavorably and that the Division 2 did nothing about it.","start":841.071,"stop":854.838,"duration":13.77},{"text":"Then, this ruthless tariff would have gone into effect unassailably, is that right?","start":854.838,"stop":860.16,"duration":5.32}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Had the Commission done nothing about it?","start":860.16,"stop":861.919,"duration":1.76},{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":861.919,"stop":862.291,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":862.291,"stop":862.604,"duration":0.31},{"text":"Well, I'm not -- I just want to know what the course of events.","start":862.604,"stop":865.609,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"That would have been --","start":865.609,"stop":865.943,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And what the Board -- what the underlying -- what the structure -- I'm trying to find out what the law, what the Interstate Commerce Act provides, what the procedure for relief is, what the power of the Commission are.","start":865.943,"stop":877.442,"duration":11.5}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":877.442,"stop":878.424,"duration":0.98},{"text":"Then, the -- I think the -- in -- I believe, Your Honor, has it correct that if -- if the Board of Suspension had decided to do nothing, the Interstate Commerce Commission itself on our appeal to -- to it to examine the action of its employees had resulted in no action, then these rates would have automatically gone into effect on September the 24th as scheduled.","start":878.424,"stop":905.912,"duration":27.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":905.912,"stop":907.165,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Now --","start":907.165,"stop":907.334,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But suppose the -- what really was done had -- suppose the course of events had been what they were, namely that the Board of Suspension rejected your protest or didn't act on it favorably, Division 2, in fact, overruled the Board and suspend it.","start":907.334,"stop":926.637,"duration":19.3},{"text":"And then, suppose Division 2 did what I have known courts to do, think of all what they have done and get together the next day and say “Let's reconsider this” someone, a member more interested or more alert or more anything or less anything, I don't care which and say, “Let's rethink this.”","start":926.637,"stop":944.532,"duration":17.9},{"text":"And the next day they say “We were all wrong about it yesterday,” and then they recall that order.","start":944.532,"stop":950.292,"duration":5.76}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"I'd like to get to that a little later.","start":950.292,"stop":951.507,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Even the Supreme Court of the United States have been known to do that.","start":951.507,"stop":954.267,"duration":2.76}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":954.267,"stop":955.167,"duration":0.9},{"text":"And I think, usually, when the Supreme Court of the United States or any other court, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, changes its mind, it says, “Why it did.”","start":955.167,"stop":963.109,"duration":7.94}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It may only or not to.","start":963.109,"stop":965.02,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"And we have the situation here, which I would like to outline further in the facts where the vice in the commission order here was that they didn't say they were wrong.","start":965.02,"stop":979.633,"duration":14.61},{"text":"The effect of their finding was and the effect of what they did subsequently was to reaffirm that they were right in the first place in their finding of probable unlawfulness, but persisted in doing -- in taking away the protection of the order which they had already said and reiterated, we were entitled to receive.","start":979.633,"stop":998.333,"duration":18.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is that?","start":998.333,"stop":999.172,"duration":0.84},{"text":"Where did they say they were -- they were still -- they still thought it ought to be suspended but they aren't going to do it?","start":999.172,"stop":1005.814,"duration":6.64},{"text":"Where did they say that?","start":1005.814,"stop":1007.583,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"They do not say that in so many words.","start":1007.583,"stop":1009.848,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well then, any kind of words.","start":1009.848,"stop":1012.778,"duration":2.93}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"If we examine page 7, we find the order which I am challenging in which it says that by an order on page 7 of the record --","start":1012.778,"stop":1029.846,"duration":17.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon.","start":1029.846,"stop":1032.464,"duration":2.62},{"text":"All right.","start":1032.464,"stop":1033.076,"duration":0.61},{"text":"Thank you.","start":1033.076,"stop":1033.744,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Page 7 of the record, the Commission refers to the order of September the 23rd and says that it entered upon an investigation concerning unlawfulness of the rates and charges.","start":1033.744,"stop":1052.05,"duration":18.31},{"text":"That consideration has been given to petitions of the respondents requesting vacation and to reply as thereto in good cause appearing.","start":1052.05,"stop":1059.568,"duration":7.52},{"text":"It is ordered that the order be set aside insofar as it suspended the operations, but the proceeding of investigation of said schedule shall continue in full force in effect.","start":1059.568,"stop":1070.711,"duration":11.14},{"text":"I say that the necessary effect of that order, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, is that they reaffirmed the findings of probable unlawfulness because, otherwise, they would not have continued to investigate schedules.","start":1070.711,"stop":1085.424,"duration":14.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, don't they have to examine the merits of the reasonableness of the order that was filed?","start":1085.424,"stop":1089.98,"duration":4.56}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1089.98,"stop":1090.567,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Didn't you protest against it?","start":1090.567,"stop":1094.277,"duration":3.71}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"But a request for a suspension, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, is not a formal complaint.","start":1094.277,"stop":1101.523,"duration":7.25}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I know, but the Commission don't know what it can decide whether a big slash in the rate is reasonable or not.","start":1101.523,"stop":1106.481,"duration":4.96}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, and if they do, sir, they are by that very act saying in effect that there is something probably unlawful with these rates and we're going to look into the matter.","start":1106.481,"stop":1118.787,"duration":12.31}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I think there's no justification for any such statement.","start":1118.787,"stop":1121.318,"duration":2.53},{"text":"They merely say that on the phase of it is a basis for us to investigative.","start":1121.318,"stop":1125.257,"duration":3.94},{"text":"It doesn't follow because you investigate to find a rate which a carrier can initiate and you may after investigation find that it's unreasonable.","start":1125.257,"stop":1133.582,"duration":8.33},{"text":"To another phase of it, it's unreasonable.","start":1133.582,"stop":1137.008,"duration":3.43},{"text":"What's the point of a long investigation if you can make that judgment very quickly?","start":1137.008,"stop":1140.853,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1140.853,"stop":1141.32,"duration":0.47},{"text":"I do not say.","start":1141.32,"stop":1142.046,"duration":0.73},{"text":"I say that -- that probable cause exists and probable cause did exist, I think or they would not have undertaken the investigation.","start":1142.046,"stop":1151.948,"duration":9.9},{"text":"The court below in its opinion --","start":1151.948,"stop":1155.823,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. -- before you get to the court below, Mr. Currie, will you get back to the date of September where --","start":1155.823,"stop":1163.447,"duration":7.62}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1163.447,"stop":1163.822,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- where the Court made the order of suspension and carry on with your narrative.","start":1163.822,"stop":1170.321,"duration":6.5}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, sir.","start":1170.321,"stop":1170.403,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I want to hear the narrative, if you please.","start":1170.403,"stop":1171.909,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":1171.909,"stop":1172.882,"duration":0.97},{"text":"The -- the Commission there, as I say, entered this order of suspension in which it found.","start":1172.882,"stop":1182.388,"duration":9.51},{"text":"It stated reasons as required under Section 15(7) that these rates would -- it is -- there is reason to believe said the Commission that these rates would, if permitted to become effective, result in rates and charges on rules and regulations and practices that would be unlawful and would violate the National Transportation Policy.","start":1182.388,"stop":1204.554,"duration":22.17},{"text":"The order then went on to suspend the schedules and to tell the railroads that neither these schedules suspended nor those sought to be ordered by the new schedules should be changed until the proceeding has been disposed off or until the period of suspension had expired or until otherwise ordered by the Commission.","start":1204.554,"stop":1224.484,"duration":19.93},{"text":"Now, there is where the man arrested until on November the 14th, 1955.","start":1224.484,"stop":1230.062,"duration":5.58},{"text":"The Commission entered the order which we challenge in the court below.","start":1230.062,"stop":1235.422,"duration":5.36},{"text":"That is the order to which -- which appears on page 7 of the record and to which I have just made reference.","start":1235.422,"stop":1243.599,"duration":8.18},{"text":"We didn't get notice of it.","start":1243.599,"stop":1246.747,"duration":3.15},{"text":"Of course, the instant date was filed but as soon as we did, we went to the District Court.","start":1246.747,"stop":1254.998,"duration":8.25},{"text":"In the meantime, we asked the Commission to weigh the rule and modify the rule and reconsider the action of Division 2 by the entire Commission.","start":1254.998,"stop":1266.165,"duration":11.17},{"text":"The -- the Commission declined to do that on November the 23rd.","start":1266.165,"stop":1272.443,"duration":6.28}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the order recites petition's requesting vacation in reply thereto.","start":1272.443,"stop":1279.187,"duration":6.74},{"text":"What was the substance of the petitions?","start":1279.187,"stop":1282.335,"duration":3.15},{"text":"That's the advance to this order, the instant date.","start":1282.335,"stop":1284.457,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"It had then advanced, sir, and the record does not show it.","start":1284.457,"stop":1287.272,"duration":2.81},{"text":"I do not have them.","start":1287.272,"stop":1288.352,"duration":1.08},{"text":"I never did see the petitions for -- for the petitions requesting vacation nor -- and -- nor the reply.","start":1288.352,"stop":1297,"duration":8.65}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, did the replies refer reply from the part of your time?","start":1297,"stop":1301.725,"duration":4.72}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"I take it so, sir, but I did not found one and I did not see the others.","start":1301.725,"stop":1306.335,"duration":4.61},{"text":"I'm sorry, and it was never --","start":1306.335,"stop":1308.63,"duration":2.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you mean that reached the cycle?","start":1308.63,"stop":1310.44,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":1310.44,"stop":1312.624,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that recital baseless where the Commission say there were a petition and replied when there weren't any?","start":1312.624,"stop":1318.033,"duration":5.41}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Brennan's question, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, was what was the substance of those petitions?","start":1318.033,"stop":1322.264,"duration":4.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But I will first want to know, was there a petition?","start":1322.264,"stop":1325.449,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sure there was.","start":1325.449,"stop":1326.475,"duration":1.03},{"text":"They (Voice Overlap) --","start":1326.475,"stop":1326.601,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Or their reply?","start":1326.601,"stop":1328.254,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sure so.","start":1328.254,"stop":1329.152,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"An order replied on behalf of the present respondents?","start":1329.152,"stop":1334.536,"duration":5.38}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"The present respondents would not --","start":1334.536,"stop":1336.291,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You represent the respondents, don't you?","start":1336.291,"stop":1338.257,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh the first respondents, yes.","start":1338.257,"stop":1339.721,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The appellees, I beg your pardon.","start":1339.721,"stop":1340.868,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"The appellees.","start":1340.868,"stop":1341.451,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In appeal.","start":1341.451,"stop":1342.242,"duration":0.79},{"text":"The appellees, were those replies on behalf of the appellees?","start":1342.242,"stop":1345.484,"duration":3.24}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"So far as I know, my -- these present appellees did not file a reply except in connection with or they were represented by their -- by their several freight bureaus.","start":1345.484,"stop":1356.187,"duration":10.7},{"text":"I didn't see them.","start":1356.187,"stop":1357.211,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it didn't -- the question isn't, if I may so, whether you saw them.","start":1357.211,"stop":1360.085,"duration":2.87},{"text":"The question is whether these appellees filed a reply?","start":1360.085,"stop":1365.486,"duration":5.4}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Then well, let's -- let us concede that they did, sir, because I'm sure that the question --","start":1365.486,"stop":1373.182,"duration":7.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That was --","start":1373.182,"stop":1373.559,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that would be -- that would be near -- most against me and I'm willing to concede that they did file replies, yes, sir.","start":1373.559,"stop":1378.327,"duration":4.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this isn't a personal matter, Mr. Currie.","start":1378.327,"stop":1386.435,"duration":8.11}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, the replies were filed, we would say and --","start":1386.435,"stop":1392.724,"duration":6.29}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, are you -- I thought you said that you received no notice of the order and I -- I would suppose if there were petitions to which replies were filed on behalf of your clients, you must have -- they must have known that there would be some action taken on the petitions.","start":1392.724,"stop":1410.987,"duration":18.26}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- what I meant was we didn't get it immediately.","start":1410.987,"stop":1414,"duration":3.01},{"text":"In other words, it wasn't -- we didn't get it on November the 14th.","start":1414,"stop":1418.037,"duration":4.04},{"text":"ASdministrative processes being what they are, it took the Commission a few days before it was able to get to my clients.","start":1418.037,"stop":1425.949,"duration":7.91},{"text":"This order, I think, is about a week it took them before the -- and now, we made no complaint about it.","start":1425.949,"stop":1432.566,"duration":6.62},{"text":"It just took about a week to get the order mimeographed and distribute it to everybody.","start":1432.566,"stop":1436.068,"duration":3.5}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"For about two months -- two months elapsed between the original order of September 23rd and this order of November 24th.","start":1436.068,"stop":1445.122,"duration":9.05}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the order was November 14th, effective November 24th, two months to be precise.","start":1445.122,"stop":1448.18,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right, November 14th and I --","start":1448.18,"stop":1449.638,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1449.638,"stop":1450.287,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right, 10 days shorter of two months.","start":1450.287,"stop":1453.037,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1453.037,"stop":1454.592,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And what I take it, Justice Brennan and I inquiring about is what took place in between?","start":1454.592,"stop":1460.573,"duration":5.98}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"The only thing that took --","start":1460.573,"stop":1461.076,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The Commission says -- the Commission says that a petition was filed and that replies were made thereto.","start":1461.076,"stop":1467.846,"duration":6.77},{"text":"I --","start":1467.846,"stop":1468.592,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1468.592,"stop":1468.896,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It could be sorry days so far as I'm concerned if the Commission would make recitals like that or unfounded in fact.","start":1468.896,"stop":1475.334,"duration":6.44}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"I do not challenge the fact that petitions were filed and replies were made.","start":1475.334,"stop":1478.6,"duration":3.27},{"text":"I say they were to the -- my -- my only ignorance, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, was that I do not know what they said and which was Mr. Justice Brennan's question what was the substance of them and I didn't know.","start":1478.6,"stop":1491.024,"duration":12.42}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, just it make it say a fair inference that there were considerations raised by those petitions answered in the replies which finally weighed by the Commission led them to vacate their order?","start":1491.024,"stop":1504.17,"duration":13.15}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that the Court might -- if -- if the Court is privileged to be indulged in the presumption I think that this would be the -- the presumption.","start":1504.17,"stop":1515.29,"duration":11.12},{"text":"That if there had been, sir, questions in that order or in the petitions which caused the Commission to change its mind and to decide that the facts which it thought existed on September the 23rd did not, in truth, exist.","start":1515.29,"stop":1531.274,"duration":15.98},{"text":"The Commission could have said so and should have said so in its order of vacation.","start":1531.274,"stop":1537.443,"duration":6.17},{"text":"So that I think the fair inference to be drawn is that there was noting in those petitions or nor in the replies which would have caused the Commission to change its mind about the reasons why these rates might have been probably involved.","start":1537.443,"stop":1551.181,"duration":13.74}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Would it make a difference to your case if they had said in explicit unambiguous language having on reconsideration and found that probably cause does not exist for suspension but no more.","start":1551.181,"stop":1562.629,"duration":11.45},{"text":"Would that have made a difference to your case?","start":1562.629,"stop":1566.316,"duration":3.69}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"I doubt that, sir.","start":1566.316,"stop":1567.478,"duration":1.16},{"text":"I think they would have had to gone farther and said, “We were in error in finding that these rates were probably unlawful.”","start":1567.478,"stop":1576.444,"duration":8.97}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose they said that, we were in error in finding these rates, would that have satisfied -- would that make a difference to your case?","start":1576.444,"stop":1583.069,"duration":6.63}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Frankfurter, I can only say, sir, that if that had been the language, I would have hesitated a long time before I had gone to court.","start":1583.069,"stop":1590.487,"duration":7.42}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Just those words and no more?","start":1590.487,"stop":1592.119,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"I would be inclined to think that I -- I would not be on various sound right now.","start":1592.119,"stop":1599.063,"duration":6.94},{"text":"However, I did not reach that point and because that wasn't what occurred.","start":1599.063,"stop":1603.525,"duration":4.46}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then that isn't the order -- I'm just -- I'm thinking if that --","start":1603.525,"stop":1605.341,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"And --","start":1605.341,"stop":1605.728,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- had been the order.","start":1605.728,"stop":1606.888,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"If that had been the -- the (Voice Overlap)","start":1606.888,"stop":1608.214,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But no more.","start":1608.214,"stop":1610.261,"duration":2.05},{"text":"No more hearings, nothing more except putting in, we now realized we were all inclined in probable cause and we'll wait until the full investigation exposes the whole problem.","start":1610.261,"stop":1620.149,"duration":9.89}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm rather inclined to think, sir, in all candor that I would not have gone to Court under those circumstances.","start":1620.149,"stop":1628.23,"duration":8.08},{"text":"I think I would have just decided that that was within the discretion of the Commission and I have a very clear opinion in my own mind that the lower -- that the court below would not have sustained this.","start":1628.23,"stop":1640.793,"duration":12.56}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"When you applied to the original order of suspension, were there answers by the railroads to that or was that ex parte?","start":1640.793,"stop":1648.926,"duration":8.13}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"No, there were replies, sir.","start":1648.926,"stop":1650.167,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"There were replies thereto?","start":1650.167,"stop":1650.964,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1650.964,"stop":1652.214,"duration":1.25},{"text":"There were replies in the conference.","start":1652.214,"stop":1652.835,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Are those -- are those in the record?","start":1652.835,"stop":1655.038,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir, no, sir.","start":1655.038,"stop":1657.867,"duration":2.83}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any reason why they can't -- Court can't have access to those, at least to the second petition and replies and what's all the mystery about it?","start":1657.867,"stop":1669.194,"duration":11.33}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"None that I know of, Mr. Justice Harlan, other than --","start":1669.194,"stop":1670.834,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"They argue in this case (Voice Overlap) unrealistic bases, it seems to me, it would --","start":1670.834,"stop":1674.873,"duration":4.04}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":1674.873,"stop":1675.335,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"If there's underlying material here in which the Commission acted in these orders as recited, why isn't it in the record?","start":1675.335,"stop":1680.842,"duration":5.51},{"text":"I don't understand it.","start":1680.842,"stop":1682.806,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Simply because we took the position and I still take it, sir, that this Court on -- nor the lower court would not be required to search the record to find a basis upon which the Commission might have acted when it didn't say it acted on any basis and that the validity of the order, of any reviewable order must be tested by the recitals in the order.","start":1682.806,"stop":1711.25,"duration":28.44},{"text":"And only if you challenge these bases for the recitals and say that there is no facts upon which that order can be based.","start":1711.25,"stop":1721.644,"duration":10.39},{"text":"Is it necessary or even appropriate that one bring up the record upon which the Commission says it acted thus thereby showing that there was no factual basis for the recital.","start":1721.644,"stop":1734.616,"duration":12.97},{"text":"But whereas here, there was no recital of any fact or what is more properly stated where they were reiterated or in effect reaffirmed findings which entitled as to certain protection and no basis for any contrary action, then the action itself is subject to attack the cause.","start":1734.616,"stop":1763.965,"duration":29.35},{"text":"It does not disclose the basis on which the action was taken.","start":1763.965,"stop":1772.283,"duration":8.32},{"text":"We went to -- to continue with the recital of the facts.","start":1772.283,"stop":1775.804,"duration":3.52},{"text":"We went then to the District Court, the Judge Atwell, the District Judge before whom the case was filed and to whom the petition for temporary restraining order was presented, declined to issue it on the ground that he didn't feel that there would be any damage done to the complainants until such time as the application for temporary injunction could be heard.","start":1775.804,"stop":1811.74,"duration":35.94},{"text":"Although the record doesn't show that the railroads were present, it does show that, on page 12, that the Government was present.","start":1811.74,"stop":1818.537,"duration":6.8},{"text":"The railroads were actually present.","start":1818.537,"stop":1820.117,"duration":1.58},{"text":"I invited them.","start":1820.117,"stop":1821.011,"duration":0.89},{"text":"They didn't show here because at that time, they had not formally intervened.","start":1821.011,"stop":1830,"duration":8.99},{"text":"Now, the proceeding went on.","start":1830,"stop":1843.922,"duration":13.92},{"text":"The dealing with the subsequent proceedings before the Commission or after the -- the Court had heard the case on December the 12th, on January the 23rd it entered its order finding that the order under attack was invalid.","start":1843.922,"stop":1862.434,"duration":18.51},{"text":"Thereafter, and by the way, the Court was pretty careful to say that they were simply -- it is simply saying that the order of September 23 could be modified.","start":1862.434,"stop":1876.254,"duration":13.82},{"text":"They weren't going to say that the Commission could not have changed its mind.","start":1876.254,"stop":1881.406,"duration":5.15},{"text":"But if they do change their mind or if it did change its mind, it had to do so under lawful means and set the matter back to the Commission with the open invitation on page 59 of the record that the Commission should -- if it wanted to set aside the order of September 23rd, do so lawfully.","start":1881.406,"stop":1904.873,"duration":23.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Which means in this case that they could say nunc pro tunc, we now insert and whereas, as then so minded, we do not find the base -- probable cause for suspending.","start":1904.873,"stop":1918.674,"duration":13.8},{"text":"We as of whatever this date is, December 25th, December 14th has --","start":1918.674,"stop":1925.41,"duration":6.74}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Or January the 23rd.","start":1925.41,"stop":1926.821,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Whatever it is, way back.","start":1926.821,"stop":1928.346,"duration":1.53},{"text":"That's what this -- that's what the practicality would mean?","start":1928.346,"stop":1931.16,"duration":2.81}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"I do not think they would have done that.","start":1931.16,"stop":1933.741,"duration":2.58},{"text":"I think that you would have to treat it as though the Commission still had the petitions for reconsideration under advisement and it could have on January the 23rd, then simply entered an order granting the petitions for reconsideration asserting the factual basis upon which it acted.","start":1933.741,"stop":1952.029,"duration":18.29},{"text":"We don't give --","start":1952.029,"stop":1953.07,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But your -- your statement doesn't -- didn't call for any factual statement.","start":1953.07,"stop":1957.765,"duration":4.7},{"text":"It merely requires a recital, an explicit language that we have -- we now find way back, not after the whole investigation.","start":1957.765,"stop":1966.227,"duration":8.46},{"text":"We find as of whatever it was, December, 1954 that there was no probably cause.","start":1966.227,"stop":1972.173,"duration":5.95},{"text":"That's all they would have to say to be according to a lawyer.","start":1972.173,"stop":1979.421,"duration":7.25}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"As I say, sir, if they -- Commission has --","start":1979.421,"stop":1981.675,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, did they say that?","start":1981.675,"stop":1983.118,"duration":1.44},{"text":"Did they --","start":1983.118,"stop":1983.175,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":1983.175,"stop":1983.807,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Did they say that in their order of November 14th?","start":1983.807,"stop":1987.692,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1987.692,"stop":1988.267,"duration":0.58},{"text":"Of course they didn't.","start":1988.267,"stop":1989.661,"duration":1.39},{"text":"They did not say that.","start":1989.661,"stop":1990.235,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"There's a -- a tribunal --","start":1990.235,"stop":1990.997,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I was asking counsel --","start":1990.997,"stop":1993.57,"duration":2.57}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"They did not say -- they did not say anything to indicate the slightest that they were dissatisfied with the order of September 23, 1955.","start":1993.57,"stop":2002.225,"duration":8.65}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If a -- if a tribunal changes its -- reverses its opinion, it means it's of the same opinion still, is that it?","start":2002.225,"stop":2012.887,"duration":10.66}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me put it this way, Mr. Justice Frankfurter.","start":2012.887,"stop":2018.207,"duration":5.32},{"text":"You may be able to change your opinion, but here in this case, the Commission was under a statutory duty and under Section 15, subsection 7 of the Interstate Commerce Act to state reasons why it would interfere with the -- with the, otherwise, invaluable right of the carrier to initiate its own rates.","start":2018.207,"stop":2042.285,"duration":24.08},{"text":"It made this statement.","start":2042.285,"stop":2044.026,"duration":1.74},{"text":"It -- it stated those reasons and those reasons were in substance that other people were going to be hurt by this publication or that there was probable cause to believe that there would be.","start":2044.026,"stop":2058.73,"duration":14.7},{"text":"As a matter of fact, I think we can agree that the only time the Commission in the exercise of sound discretion can interfere with the carrier's right to publish its own rates is because it has determined that somebody is going to get hurt.","start":2058.73,"stop":2075.647,"duration":16.92},{"text":"Otherwise, there's no reason to interfere with what the carrier may do.","start":2075.647,"stop":2080.054,"duration":4.41},{"text":"And once the Commission has found that there exist a situation, which causes -- which may injure someone and has decided to take action to protect that someone.","start":2080.054,"stop":2096.719,"duration":16.66},{"text":"Then, if the Commission decides that it is wrong about that that those facts do not exist.","start":2096.719,"stop":2105.922,"duration":9.2},{"text":"I think it owes to that person the same duty.","start":2105.922,"stop":2109.781,"duration":3.86},{"text":"Having once found that those rights are to be protected, the Commission is under a mandatory duty to protect them and if it finds it's in error about that, it owes to the -- to the person whose rights are thus being not longer protected, the duty to say -- to give the reasons for it just as though to the same standards it had to tell the carrier in the first place.","start":2109.781,"stop":2134.185,"duration":24.4},{"text":"I think that's just with simple fairness and a necessary corollary to the suspension power.","start":2134.185,"stop":2140.787,"duration":6.6},{"text":"Those things, the Commission did not do.","start":2140.787,"stop":2143.338,"duration":2.55},{"text":"As a matter of fact, it seemed to have regarded it, just as though -- just as the District Court did in the Western supply, the Western Electric Company against Cinema Supplies Company, a case by the Sixth Circuit, in which the Court seemed to have found on a temporary injunction, mind you.","start":2143.338,"stop":2163.582,"duration":20.24},{"text":"It found all of the facts in favor of the plaintiffs that would entitle the plaintiffs to the injunctive relief sought.","start":2163.582,"stop":2172.99,"duration":9.41},{"text":"And then said that we have balanced the equities and they decided that we will not issue the injunction because under the -- all of the balancing of equities, it would not be right to do it.","start":2172.99,"stop":2183.677,"duration":10.69},{"text":"And the Circuit Court of Appeals for the Fifth -- for the Sixth Circuit reversed and said that when a court has made -- when a case for temporary injunction is clearly made out.","start":2183.677,"stop":2193.872,"duration":10.19},{"text":"It does not lie within the power of a court, though it'd be discretionary to deny the remedy.","start":2193.872,"stop":2200.986,"duration":7.11},{"text":"And certainly whereas here, the facts which the Commission found to exist and which it did not take away in its subsequent order as it left those facts still enforced by its subsequent order -- by the very nature of the order.","start":2200.986,"stop":2224.632,"duration":23.65},{"text":"It's simply saying that were just not going to grant the remedy any longer.","start":2224.632,"stop":2230.682,"duration":6.05},{"text":"That was our complaint and that was the real vice in the argument, in the order of the Commission.","start":2230.682,"stop":2236.218,"duration":5.54}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I gather what you would have wanted the order to say or something in fact but we were wrong when we thought that somebody was going to be hurt, to use your language.","start":2236.218,"stop":2247.323,"duration":11.11},{"text":"And that now, we're satisfied that no one will be hurt and we're satisfied that no one will be hurt for the following reasons, is that it?","start":2247.323,"stop":2254.952,"duration":7.63}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that -- that would have been much stronger.","start":2254.952,"stop":2257.701,"duration":2.75},{"text":"Now, mind you --","start":2257.701,"stop":2258.428,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Much stronger?","start":2258.428,"stop":2259.6,"duration":1.17},{"text":"Wouldn't that have been enough?","start":2259.6,"stop":2261.241,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"So far as I can now determine, sir, that would have been enough.","start":2261.241,"stop":2264.403,"duration":3.16},{"text":"I -- I say that simply because I have done -- I have briefed this case and have -- have satisfied myself about the applicable principles of the law, relating them only, sir, to the facts that are here present.","start":2264.403,"stop":2281.226,"duration":16.82},{"text":"I would not want to hazard a -- an opinion as to what the law might be where the facts differ.","start":2281.226,"stop":2289.022,"duration":7.8},{"text":"Although, I can appreciate that Your Honors must take those things into account.","start":2289.022,"stop":2294.356,"duration":5.33},{"text":"I would not want to be unhelpful by making a wrong guess.","start":2294.356,"stop":2298.867,"duration":4.51},{"text":"And I would say that based on what I now know, I would say that would have been enough having that been the situation.","start":2298.867,"stop":2307.433,"duration":8.57},{"text":"Certainly, it's the point --","start":2307.433,"stop":2307.767,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- you say they could have -- if they had found that without any hearings and without any evidence, without any additional information, that would be enough?","start":2307.767,"stop":2317.775,"duration":10.01}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2317.775,"stop":2318.145,"duration":0.37},{"text":"Then -- then we might have had -- we might have been back in the courthouse.","start":2318.145,"stop":2321.469,"duration":3.32},{"text":"As a matter of fact, I remember telling Judge Brown who asked the question about, suppose that -- suppose we send this back to the Commission and the Commission makes findings, what are you going to do then?","start":2321.469,"stop":2332.808,"duration":11.34},{"text":"And I had said to him that so far as I am presently informed, there's nothing in those petitions that would change the -- that would change the -- that should have changed the Commission's mind and we might well be back to challenge the action of the Commission on the ground that the action had no factual basis even though the facts were recited.","start":2332.808,"stop":2353.125,"duration":20.32},{"text":"And we could have --","start":2353.125,"stop":2353.318,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the petitions you referred to are not here, you say?","start":2353.318,"stop":2357.606,"duration":4.29}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir, no, sir.","start":2357.606,"stop":2358.389,"duration":0.78},{"text":"As I said, I did not consider it necessary to bring them up in the court below.","start":2358.389,"stop":2362.85,"duration":4.46},{"text":"The -- the absence of them was not challenged in the court below.","start":2362.85,"stop":2367.866,"duration":5.02},{"text":"The Commission made no effort to -- to justify its action either in the court below and here, I mean as a de facto matter.","start":2367.866,"stop":2378.211,"duration":10.34},{"text":"The -- the whole issue of whether or not the Commission was, as a matter of fact, and truth justified based on the petitions has never been presented.","start":2378.211,"stop":2387.576,"duration":9.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yet, you're asking us to say that the Commission was baseless in making such a determination.","start":2387.576,"stop":2392.509,"duration":4.93}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"On the authority of -- of other decisions, yes sir, by this Court because this Court has consistently held that that an order of an administrative agency must -- the order itself must disclose the basis upon which the action was taken.","start":2392.509,"stop":2409.331,"duration":16.82}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"This Court has never made any such statement because it couldn't.","start":2409.331,"stop":2413.1,"duration":3.77},{"text":"It must have made it with reference to a particular agency, with reference to particular proceeding on a particular record.","start":2413.1,"stop":2420.157,"duration":7.06},{"text":"It doesn't make and I don't believe it ever has said in this blanket way because if there's one thing that's to be said about the relation of the Courts to the -- to the administrative agency that these are rowdily speaking ad hoc situations.","start":2420.157,"stop":2437.038,"duration":16.88},{"text":"The idea of saying that this -- that this Court has ever pronounced that it can never led an administrative order by unless as we know what all the facts were, particularly when the facts aren't broad here for us to determine whether the administrative agency acted with the utmost reason.","start":2437.038,"stop":2451.977,"duration":14.94}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"What I am trying to impart to the Court, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, was simply that it seems to be the rules so far as I have been able to determine that when -- when an administrative order is challenged, the basis upon which the order was made must appear on the face of the record.","start":2451.977,"stop":2479.287,"duration":27.31}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That is not so, in the (Inaudible) cases which ought not to be unknown to you, this Court held the Commission could act without anything before it, anything and give no reason.","start":2479.287,"stop":2497.213,"duration":17.93}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, to deal with the factual situation again, the -- the proceeding continued before the Interstate Commerce Commission, resulting on June the 25th, 1956 in an order terminating the proceedings and finding the rates to be lawful or reasonably compensatory to the carriers and that in -- incidentally, I should add this that on April the 23rd, the -- the suspension order of September 23 which had been revived by the order of the District Court expired by reason of its own terms.","start":2497.213,"stop":2539.981,"duration":42.77},{"text":"On April the 24th, the railroads republished the tariffs and the rates that were under suspension theretofore, the rates that should -- that were originally scheduled to go into effect on September the 24th.","start":2539.981,"stop":2555.125,"duration":15.14},{"text":"These reduced rates became effective on April the 24th, 1956.","start":2555.125,"stop":2560.525,"duration":5.4}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Where -- what -- where is that order now?","start":2560.525,"stop":2563.182,"duration":2.66},{"text":"Was that challenged?","start":2563.182,"stop":2566.159,"duration":2.98}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2566.159,"stop":2566.719,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Does that -- is that the order you say that after investigation, the Commission decided that the rates were fair?","start":2566.719,"stop":2575.722,"duration":9}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2575.722,"stop":2576.056,"duration":0.33},{"text":"When the Commission finally finished its investigation on June the 25th, 1956, and that proceeding is reported in 298 I.C.C. 721.","start":2576.056,"stop":2588.113,"duration":12.06},{"text":"That happened after the case was heard --","start":2588.113,"stop":2589.731,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"How did that leave the comparative rates of the bus lines and the --","start":2589.731,"stop":2594.738,"duration":5.01}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"That leaves them presently, sir.","start":2594.738,"stop":2596.489,"duration":1.75},{"text":"That leaves presently, sir.","start":2596.489,"stop":2597.746,"duration":1.26},{"text":"By the way, I should add as a matter of -- of information that ultimately, the Commission found that our rates were all right too.","start":2597.746,"stop":2605.427,"duration":7.68},{"text":"And so that presently, the -- the relationship between the motor carriers and the rail carriers is that the rate from the Panhandle to -- to Akron by rail is $1.33 per hundred and the rate from -- by motor carrier from the same points -- between the same point is $1.4785.","start":2605.427,"stop":2627.411,"duration":21.98},{"text":"We have been permitted to meet the older rail rate, but we have not tried to meet the new rail rate.","start":2627.411,"stop":2635.102,"duration":7.69},{"text":"We can't because we just can't justify it.","start":2635.102,"stop":2638.914,"duration":3.81},{"text":"We know the Commission would -- would -- our over the road cost of operation just wouldn't meet and we just can't do it.","start":2638.914,"stop":2646.435,"duration":7.52},{"text":"So, we have not tried to meet that rate.","start":2646.435,"stop":2648.052,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"So that means that -- that means then according to the findings I presume that railroads can carry cheaper than you can by reason of the inherent advantages that they have over you in that connection?","start":2648.052,"stop":2660.19,"duration":12.14}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"I assume so, sir.","start":2660.19,"stop":2661.164,"duration":0.97},{"text":"At least they found that -- that the rails -- it was compensatory for the rails and we have decided in our managerial discretion that it's not compensatory for us.","start":2661.164,"stop":2670.353,"duration":9.19}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And that order -- that order is not challenged with reference to the rail rates.","start":2670.353,"stop":2673.948,"duration":3.59}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, no sir.","start":2673.948,"stop":2674.682,"duration":0.73},{"text":"Not now.","start":2674.682,"stop":2675.582,"duration":0.9},{"text":"It is -- it is finished.","start":2675.582,"stop":2677.874,"duration":2.29},{"text":"That is why, Mr. Justice Black, that this case is moot.","start":2677.874,"stop":2682.373,"duration":4.5}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"How much difference is it between them?","start":2682.373,"stop":2684.418,"duration":2.05},{"text":"What was the difference between your rates at the time that the Commission first suspended this order?","start":2684.418,"stop":2690.29,"duration":5.87}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Five and fifteen one hundred cents, sir.","start":2690.29,"stop":2693.064,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And what's the difference now after all these hearings?","start":2693.064,"stop":2695.689,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Fourteen and eighty-five one hundred cents, sir.","start":2695.689,"stop":2703.483,"duration":7.79},{"text":"That's still the differential over -- under up.","start":2703.483,"stop":2707.38,"duration":3.9},{"text":"We do not have the advantage of this traffic any longer, sir, no matter what this Court may do with this proceeding.","start":2707.38,"stop":2714.708,"duration":7.33},{"text":"This appellee, motor carriers have nothing to gain nor to lose.","start":2714.708,"stop":2718.988,"duration":4.28}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But why -- why are you defending this?","start":2718.988,"stop":2720.943,"duration":1.96},{"text":"I don't follow it.","start":2720.943,"stop":2723.073,"duration":2.13},{"text":"I mean, what --","start":2723.073,"stop":2724.702,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, sir --","start":2724.702,"stop":2724.842,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- what does it make to your clients what happens to those seven months.","start":2724.842,"stop":2730.44,"duration":5.6}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"It made this difference.","start":2730.44,"stop":2731.745,"duration":1.3},{"text":"I -- I just didn't feel, sir, that as an officer of this Court and been having -- been successful in the court below that it would -- it was quite the discharge in my duty as counsel nor my client to make no effort to defend a -- a situation which we regarded as correct at the time.","start":2731.745,"stop":2758.735,"duration":26.99}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But as a practical matter, if the appellants win here, you lose nothing.","start":2758.735,"stop":2764.652,"duration":5.92}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, sir.","start":2764.652,"stop":2765.414,"duration":0.76},{"text":"We have already lost -- what we lose otherwise.","start":2765.414,"stop":2768.782,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Not only --","start":2768.782,"stop":2768.855,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct Mr. Justice Brennan, we would not lose anymore than we've already lost.","start":2768.855,"stop":2775.5,"duration":6.64}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"As I understood from what you said a minute ago, you're here out of regards for your duty to the Court as a lawyer and yet you argue the case is moot so it's our business to throw out the case.","start":2775.5,"stop":2789.27,"duration":13.77}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":2789.27,"stop":2790.575,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That you argue the case is moot.","start":2790.575,"stop":2793,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2793,"stop":2793.176,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And that -- so that your duty as a counsel to this Court is to bring a case here that you say we should throw out.","start":2793.176,"stop":2798.662,"duration":5.49}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"I did not, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, bring it here.","start":2798.662,"stop":2801.286,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What?","start":2801.286,"stop":2801.968,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"I did not bring it here.","start":2801.968,"stop":2802.533,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I know, but the case is -- the case is now decided so that you created a situation -- we've got a situation in which a principle of law is laid down, which you now say is moot, the decision.","start":2802.533,"stop":2815.793,"duration":13.26}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, I concede that my duty as counsel, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, to tell the Court that I consider it moot.","start":2815.793,"stop":2822.397,"duration":6.6},{"text":"I -- I would like to say that it's not moot and I would like to say that it ought to be affirmed on its merits, but I do not really, sir, as a lawyer that I can truthfully say that I think that it is not moot.","start":2822.397,"stop":2835.145,"duration":12.75},{"text":"And it occurred to me that if counsel is to discharge his full duties to the Court, it ought to disclose to the Court any facts and circumstances which might render the case moot because the Court certainly does not want to spend its time and efforts and energies in deciding controversies.","start":2835.145,"stop":2855.545,"duration":20.4},{"text":"The -- where the logic of events has turned the investigation into an autopsy, instead of a determination of litigations.","start":2855.545,"stop":2862.773,"duration":7.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But you must have had a live litigation, some interest of a client and not merely abstract devotion to law that brought you in the Court, is that right?","start":2862.773,"stop":2875.277,"duration":12.5}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"I can answer that question only this way, sir, because I'm not sure that I have quite followed, Your Honor.","start":2875.277,"stop":2881.445,"duration":6.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But you can't.","start":2881.445,"stop":2881.953,"duration":0.51},{"text":"Lawyers can, no matter how strongly they feel, that they want a further sound law.","start":2881.953,"stop":2888.923,"duration":6.97},{"text":"They cannot just come into a court and say, \"I want to promote the just development of the law.\"","start":2888.923,"stop":2894.094,"duration":5.17},{"text":"Their client must have an earthly interest.","start":2894.094,"stop":2897.634,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir, the -- now, my client and by the way, only one of these seven felt that he wanted to spend the time and money to get in and justify the action of the court below, that's why I'm here.","start":2897.634,"stop":2914.223,"duration":16.59},{"text":"We have this feeling about it, sir, that if it's not moot and the other side of the case, it isn't moot.","start":2914.223,"stop":2921.668,"duration":7.45},{"text":"And we do not want to see the case reversed for -- just by a -- as a result of a default.","start":2921.668,"stop":2928.139,"duration":6.47}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You are saying -- you are claiming that it was not moot when you filed a suit but it's --","start":2928.139,"stop":2933.046,"duration":4.91}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"It certainly was a very live one when we filed the suit.","start":2933.046,"stop":2935.784,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But -- but has become --","start":2935.784,"stop":2937.236,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"It become moot -- it became moot -- I'm sorry.","start":2937.236,"stop":2940.276,"duration":3.04},{"text":"It became moot on April the 23rd when the suspension order which we asked which was entered for our protection expired by reason of the seven-month statutory period.","start":2940.276,"stop":2950.197,"duration":9.92}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And you -- you are saying that so far as you are concerned as a litigant, so far as the admission is concerned as a litigant, no longer any -- any live controversy between you and them --","start":2950.197,"stop":2963.178,"duration":12.98}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"That's --","start":2963.178,"stop":2963.287,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- whatever obligations might be imposed on railroads or somebody else.","start":2963.287,"stop":2967.768,"duration":4.48}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct and there's no -- and there's no live controversy so far as the railroads are concerned, either, sir, in my opinion.","start":2967.768,"stop":2974.803,"duration":7.03}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the higher rate is now the legal rate.","start":2974.803,"stop":2977.496,"duration":2.69}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2977.496,"stop":2978.397,"duration":0.9},{"text":"The lower rate is now the legal rate, sir.","start":2978.397,"stop":2980.953,"duration":2.56}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I mean, the charge -- they charged too little and what is the law -- what was found to be the lawful rate, is that right?And therefore, there was an undercharge and therefore if the railroad doesn't collect it, it's a rebate.","start":2980.953,"stop":2995.582,"duration":14.63}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Frankfurter, I wonder if there is any liability on the -- to me, it seems this, that to say that the railroad is liable to collect the undercharge, it's just a -- a use of word.","start":2995.582,"stop":3010.635,"duration":15.05},{"text":"Actually, it would seem to me that -- if that -- what the railroads are in effect saying is that if this -- if the action of the Court is upheld, we're entitled to more money, which I do not perceive to be a -- a detriment.","start":3010.635,"stop":3027.395,"duration":16.76},{"text":"They're entitled to more money.","start":3027.395,"stop":3028.725,"duration":1.33},{"text":"It isn't --","start":3028.725,"stop":3028.783,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But it's something alive.","start":3028.783,"stop":3030.178,"duration":1.39},{"text":"That's what -- as I had to consider here for many years, that's what most of these rails are about, money on one side or another.","start":3030.178,"stop":3037.133,"duration":6.95}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"I --","start":3037.133,"stop":3038.689,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Currie, we've been --","start":3038.689,"stop":3039.388,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3039.388,"stop":3039.821,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- getting your argument on mootness in -- in very fragmentary manner.","start":3039.821,"stop":3045.281,"duration":5.46},{"text":"Would you mind stating your position?","start":3045.281,"stop":3047.984,"duration":2.7},{"text":"You only have a few minutes more.","start":3047.984,"stop":3049.701,"duration":1.72},{"text":"Would you mind stating your brief on the mootness in this case?","start":3049.701,"stop":3050.881,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"I'd be -- I'd be glad to, sir.","start":3050.881,"stop":3052.707,"duration":1.83},{"text":"I'll try to answer the questions and that may have been why.","start":3052.707,"stop":3057.931,"duration":5.22}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3057.931,"stop":3058.241,"duration":0.31},{"text":"I am not criticizing you at all.","start":3058.241,"stop":3059.998,"duration":1.76},{"text":"You were answering questions.","start":3059.998,"stop":3063.282,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, my brief -- let me say it this way, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":3063.282,"stop":3069.526,"duration":6.24},{"text":"This proceeding involves only one question.","start":3069.526,"stop":3077.714,"duration":8.19},{"text":"Here, the Commission issued and admitted a valid suspension order.","start":3077.714,"stop":3082.115,"duration":4.4},{"text":"It suspended certain rate schedules.","start":3082.115,"stop":3085.737,"duration":3.62},{"text":"Thereafter, it attempted to set aside that suspension order.","start":3085.737,"stop":3093.065,"duration":7.33},{"text":"The order -- the -- the District Court said that that attempt was ineffectual and that the suspension order was still in full force and effect.","start":3093.065,"stop":3107.236,"duration":14.17},{"text":"Subsequently, the suspension order had expired by its own terms.","start":3107.236,"stop":3112.136,"duration":4.9},{"text":"It was not a continuing order.","start":3112.136,"stop":3114.563,"duration":2.43},{"text":"It is not a short-term order capable of repetition.","start":3114.563,"stop":3118.93,"duration":4.37},{"text":"The power of the Commission over that order was exhausted when it expired by its own terms because the statute stopped it.","start":3118.93,"stop":3127.285,"duration":8.36},{"text":"Still later, the Commission proceeded with its investigation and has entered a final order, finally terminating all matters at issue between this, these appellees, the railroads and of course the Commission.","start":3127.285,"stop":3148.247,"duration":20.96},{"text":"This proceeding attempts only to ask this Court at this late date to decide whether the Commission had power to vacate an order which by subsequent events has already been vacated.","start":3148.247,"stop":3165.186,"duration":16.94},{"text":"Now, suppose that this Court says “Yes, you had the power to vacate that order.”","start":3165.186,"stop":3171.342,"duration":6.16},{"text":"Now, what possible good is it?","start":3171.342,"stop":3176.505,"duration":5.16},{"text":"It solves nothing.","start":3176.505,"stop":3178.817,"duration":2.31},{"text":"The order is already extinct.","start":3178.817,"stop":3181.508,"duration":2.69},{"text":"It has already expired.","start":3181.508,"stop":3183.812,"duration":2.3},{"text":"It is nothing except as a guide for future conduct.","start":3183.812,"stop":3190.258,"duration":6.45}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"What about the reparations?","start":3190.258,"stop":3192.528,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"There are no reparations, Mr. Justice Clark, in this case.","start":3192.528,"stop":3198.691,"duration":6.16},{"text":"The only thing that you have here is a situation where the railroads might say that they are entitled to collect some additional money from the -- from the shippers in the event we are right.","start":3198.691,"stop":3211.598,"duration":12.91}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"The shippers wouldn't want to pay, would they?","start":3211.598,"stop":3213.771,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"I have not been advised.","start":3213.771,"stop":3215.271,"duration":1.5},{"text":"I would assume, sir that the shippers wouldn't want to pay, although, as I pointed out in the brief, these shippers were there.","start":3215.271,"stop":3223.007,"duration":7.74},{"text":"They were present in the court below.","start":3223.007,"stop":3224.956,"duration":1.95},{"text":"One of them made an affidavit in lieu of testimony in this case representing an association that ships 95% of all the carbon black.So, they knew what the facts were and they knew what the situation was at that time.","start":3224.956,"stop":3238.743,"duration":13.79},{"text":"I would say --","start":3238.743,"stop":3238.946,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, the position in the -- perhaps I'm wrong that the Commission or the railroad is one, provided there were up to seven weeks period between the date and the issuance of this vacation is commenced and the issuance of the injunction by the Court in which the railroad is charging the lower rate.","start":3238.946,"stop":3262.251,"duration":23.31}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, that's correct.","start":3262.251,"stop":3262.7,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Presumably it's correct, that's legal, it's valid.","start":3262.7,"stop":3266.611,"duration":3.91},{"text":"Now, they should have been charging during those seven weeks the higher rate.","start":3266.611,"stop":3270.761,"duration":4.15},{"text":"So now, they would be obliged, they say, (Inaudible) to go to the shippers and say, “Look, we charged you lower rates.","start":3270.761,"stop":3278.717,"duration":7.96},{"text":"We should have charged higher and we have to charge this higher rate.”","start":3278.717,"stop":3282.279,"duration":3.56},{"text":"The shippers would say, “Well, look, we've paid beyond to the order of the Court.”","start":3282.279,"stop":3286.554,"duration":4.28},{"text":"So, there'd be a controversy between the railroad and the shippers as to whether or not the -- the (Voice Overlap) --","start":3286.554,"stop":3291.058,"duration":4.5}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3291.058,"stop":3291.898,"duration":0.84},{"text":"Mr. Justice Clark that's -- that's not quite the -- the way it is.","start":3291.898,"stop":3296.31,"duration":4.41},{"text":"Under the order of the Court, they collected the higher rate, you see, and not the lower rate so that they did not --","start":3296.31,"stop":3305.419,"duration":9.11}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"But the order of the Court didn't come into effect until --","start":3305.419,"stop":3308.9,"duration":3.48}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"On --","start":3308.9,"stop":3309.067,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"-- January (Inaudible)","start":3309.067,"stop":3310.135,"duration":1.07},{"text":"So, during the seven weeks, they were collecting the lower rate, were they not?","start":3310.135,"stop":3313.922,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"During the seven weeks period, they were collecting the lower rates but the shippers couldn't defend on the ground we were paying you under the order of the Court because there wasn't any order of the Court.","start":3313.922,"stop":3321.48,"duration":7.56},{"text":"They were paying only reduced -- the reduced rate.","start":3321.48,"stop":3325.04,"duration":3.56},{"text":"Now, let me say this.","start":3325.04,"stop":3326.137,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"The order of the Court --","start":3326.137,"stop":3326.286,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's to say what the railroads were saying, “We were -- at that time, depending on the order of the Commission and we've charged them the lower rate, (Inaudible)","start":3326.286,"stop":3335.068,"duration":8.78}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3335.068,"stop":3335.622,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"So, they -- the shippers would come in and say, “Well, look, the Court vacated that ab initio so you don't have any -- that's not a valid order, but you have a conflict according to the railroad, not just during the --","start":3335.622,"stop":3350.454,"duration":14.83}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that, sir, and I -- I think there are two answers to it.","start":3350.454,"stop":3354.215,"duration":3.76},{"text":"In the first place, those people are not parties to this suit and as I see the rule of mootness as laid down by prior decision to this Court.","start":3354.215,"stop":3363.255,"duration":9.04},{"text":"This controversy has to be determined or has to be judged on whether or not there's anything that the parties to this controversy stand to gain or lose by it.","start":3363.255,"stop":3373.918,"duration":10.66},{"text":"Second, if there be any -- three things -- secondly, if this Court finds that this case is moot and vacates the judgment of the court below, as it usually does, you are going to have the -- all of that situation will be eliminated.","start":3373.918,"stop":3398.373,"duration":24.45}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Would be the same as though there had never been a lawsuit.","start":3398.373,"stop":3401.095,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3401.095,"stop":3402.182,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap)","start":3402.182,"stop":3402.313,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Would be the same as though there have been -- never been a law suit.","start":3402.313,"stop":3404.768,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Did the parties have any right of action against the railroad and to be told to what's been done already?","start":3404.768,"stop":3410.817,"duration":6.05}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, thirdly, any controversy that can be settled between the shippers and receivers of the freight and the railroads could not be settled in this Court.","start":3410.817,"stop":3424.153,"duration":13.34},{"text":"As a matter of fact, if the railroads feel that it would be unjust for them to collect the undercharges that might exist, all they need do is to apply to the Interstate Commerce Commission on the informal docket for a relief from -- and for permission to weigh the undercharges.","start":3424.153,"stop":3442.099,"duration":17.95},{"text":"That's frequently done because it operates this way that if they collect the undercharges, the Commission might award reparation back to the shipper so as an administrative shortcut when they have a situation which the rails and carriers and the shippers think is obviously unfair, they simply go to the Commission.","start":3442.099,"stop":3461.219,"duration":19.12},{"text":"The Commission -- the Commission decide that it would be unfair and that they would award reparation if collected, they said to take the shortcut and authorize the railroads to weigh the undercharge in the first instance.","start":3461.219,"stop":3472.114,"duration":10.89}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it can't be that there's a real controversy if they go before the Commission, but there is no controversy here.","start":3472.114,"stop":3481.331,"duration":9.22},{"text":"If you say they could get this fixed up or somehow arranged by getting proper relief before the Commission, it must be something with reference to which relief is given.","start":3481.331,"stop":3491.269,"duration":9.94}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that maybe --","start":3491.269,"stop":3491.519,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It says something -- which relief is to be given then it's a live controversy.","start":3491.519,"stop":3495.448,"duration":3.93}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it relief against you or relief against somebody else?","start":3495.448,"stop":3497.413,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3497.413,"stop":3498.124,"duration":0.71},{"text":"No reliefs again.","start":3498.124,"stop":3498.913,"duration":0.79},{"text":"There'd be no relief against me, sir.","start":3498.913,"stop":3501.074,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The question of mootness doesn't mean that both of them -- we got the railroads here.","start":3501.074,"stop":3505.729,"duration":4.65},{"text":"They've got an interest, but you say it's a lie.","start":3505.729,"stop":3508.286,"duration":2.56},{"text":"They can get it arranged and taken care of by going to the Commission.","start":3508.286,"stop":3512.083,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I --","start":3512.083,"stop":3512.275,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you affected by what happens here?","start":3512.275,"stop":3514.44,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"I simply say, sir, that -- that the railroads have nothing to lose.","start":3514.44,"stop":3519.198,"duration":4.76},{"text":"They have no liability.","start":3519.198,"stop":3520.265,"duration":1.07},{"text":"They're not liable for any reparation under this.","start":3520.265,"stop":3526.458,"duration":6.19},{"text":"In -- in that connection, Mr. Chief -- Mr. Justice Frankfurter, the decision of this Court in Alejandrino against Quezon which just came to my attention yesterday, it's in 271 U.S. 528.","start":3526.458,"stop":3540.743,"duration":14.28},{"text":"The -- this Court did say in that connection that it must be with the term of office, I mean this period of suspension of the term of office having expired, the case was moved even though the question of whether the man was entitled to his salary during that time have not been determined and was still left to be determined.","start":3540.743,"stop":3562.228,"duration":21.49},{"text":"It may be persuasive.","start":3562.228,"stop":3564.372,"duration":2.14},{"text":"I -- I simply want to conclude my remarks this way, if -- may it please the Court, because my time is about up.","start":3564.372,"stop":3573.789,"duration":9.42},{"text":"That the brief -- my brief here indicates very clearly that if this still presents a justiciable controversy, the action of the court below needs to be affirmed.","start":3573.789,"stop":3589.434,"duration":15.64},{"text":"The order was reviewable.","start":3589.434,"stop":3593.022,"duration":3.59},{"text":"It's impact upon the petitioners there were just as definite and certain as it ever would be when we went to the Court.","start":3593.022,"stop":3601.287,"duration":8.26},{"text":"The action of the Commission, I think as disclosed by the record, was an arbitrary action and in truth, it is worthy of some note that the -- that neither the briefs nor the argument make any real effort to justify de facto what the Commission did.","start":3601.287,"stop":3621.579,"duration":20.29},{"text":"They spend their time arguing that it was not reviewable.","start":3621.579,"stop":3627.949,"duration":6.37},{"text":"The question of the injunction of the rates is one which I think was a necessary consequence that would follow the -- judging the invalidity of the order.","start":3627.949,"stop":3638.617,"duration":10.67},{"text":"In other words, once we concede that the order was -- was invalid and that the suspension order was thereby still left in -- sorry.","start":3638.617,"stop":3649.535,"duration":10.92}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You may finish your sentence (Voice Overlap).","start":3649.535,"stop":3650.906,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph W. Currie","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":3650.906,"stop":3653.114,"duration":2.21},{"text":"Then we have -- then, we must say that the Court having found that the order was void, then these rates were published in contravention of the valid suspension order.","start":3653.114,"stop":3664.213,"duration":11.1},{"text":"And therefore, the Court would be under a duty as a necessary parallel to order that rates filed in contravention of invalid suspension order be set aside and not used.","start":3664.213,"stop":3675.439,"duration":11.23},{"text":"I thank you.","start":3675.439,"stop":3694.7,"duration":19.26}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Mar  4 - 5, 1957","petitioner":"","respondent":"","docket":"125","citation":"352 US 1028 (1957)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/352/1028","lowerCourt":"","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Mar 11, 1957"}